753
00:35:10,625 --> 00:35:11,764
- We're leaving. We're leaving.
- What?

754
00:35:11,902 --> 00:35:13,111
- Got to go. Got to go.
- What?

755
00:35:13,249 --> 00:35:14,422
- Got to go.
- What are you talk...

756
00:35:14,560 --> 00:35:15,699
- Oh, God. I'm so sorry.
- Hi. Uh...

757
00:35:15,837 --> 00:35:16,942
- Excuse me.
- What do you mean?

758
00:35:17,080 --> 00:35:18,599
- You mean busting out?
- Yep.

759
00:35:18,737 --> 00:35:20,048
- Wh-What's wrong with you?
- What's wrong is I have

760
00:35:20,187 --> 00:35:21,843
a very uncooperative
boyfriend right...

761
00:35:25,364 --> 00:35:27,918
- Oh, you got to be kidding me.
- What? What did I do?

762
00:35:28,056 --> 00:35:29,506
You know exactly
what I'm talking about.

763
00:35:29,644 --> 00:35:31,370
What did I do? Maggie.

764
00:35:32,716 --> 00:35:33,855
Shoes. Shoes, shoes.

765
00:35:33,993 --> 00:35:35,512
Yeah, sure.

766
00:35:35,650 --> 00:35:37,273
- Here.
- Thank you.

767
00:35:39,516 --> 00:35:41,449
How's it going?

768
00:35:49,630 --> 00:35:51,632
♪ ♪

769
00:35:59,605 --> 00:36:01,366
WARDEX?

770
00:36:01,504 --> 00:36:04,852
Stands for Waived Reporting
Development and Extraction.

771
00:36:06,129 --> 00:36:07,682
Of what?

772
00:36:24,872 --> 00:36:28,738
Homestead Air Force Base
in Florida, 1973.

773
00:36:29,877 --> 00:36:31,465
Who's the guy with Nixon?

774
00:36:31,603 --> 00:36:33,260
Big TV star in the '50s.

775
00:36:33,398 --> 00:36:35,227
Nixon wanted to impress him.

776
00:36:44,512 --> 00:36:46,514
♪ ♪

777
00:37:06,016 --> 00:37:08,053
♪ ♪

778
00:37:23,102 --> 00:37:24,794
Are they children?

779
00:37:24,932 --> 00:37:26,416
No.

780
00:37:29,557 --> 00:37:32,491
Are they... people?

781
00:37:32,629 --> 00:37:34,390
No.

782
00:37:37,979 --> 00:37:39,636
Are they human?

783
00:37:52,787 --> 00:37:54,893
This next part's hard to watch.

784
00:37:56,481 --> 00:37:59,277
It's what Hugo showed me
that got me into this.

785
00:38:00,830 --> 00:38:02,038
Okay?

786
00:38:07,906 --> 00:38:09,356
Okay.

787
00:38:10,909 --> 00:38:12,359
[taps key]

788
00:38:12,497 --> 00:38:14,119
MED TECH 1 [on video]:
We're gonna need vitals.

789
00:38:14,257 --> 00:38:15,638
- We've got no baseline.
- [overlapping chatter on video]

790
00:38:15,776 --> 00:38:17,225
MED TECH 2:
Pulse ox can't read.

791
00:38:17,364 --> 00:38:18,882
- No standard landmarks...
- MED TECH 3: Ketamine?

792
00:38:19,020 --> 00:38:20,263
- Four to six milligrams?
- SCANLON: No more sedatives.

793
00:38:20,401 --> 00:38:21,989
I want baseline
stress data first.

794
00:38:22,127 --> 00:38:23,991
MED TECH 4: Shift your grip.
Secure the ankles.

795
00:38:24,129 --> 00:38:26,511
- [clicking vocalizations]
- Stabilize head and right arm.

796
00:38:26,649 --> 00:38:28,858
[shrieks]

797
00:38:28,996 --> 00:38:30,860
[distressed shrieking, clicking]

798
00:38:30,998 --> 00:38:32,240
MED TECH 3:
Head's moving too much.

799
00:38:32,379 --> 00:38:33,932
I need a padded restraint.

800
00:38:34,070 --> 00:38:36,106
SCANLON: I have it.
I need cerebrospinal fluid.

801
00:38:36,244 --> 00:38:38,523
Advance the needle
18 centimeters,

802
00:38:38,661 --> 00:38:40,283
- ventral to the medulla.
- [shuddering breaths]

803
00:38:40,421 --> 00:38:42,527
MED TECH 1: It's in distress.
Administering propofol.

804
00:38:42,665 --> 00:38:44,632
SCANLON:
Negative. No anesthesia.

805
00:38:44,770 --> 00:38:46,703
We lost one that way.
Do it now.

806
00:38:46,841 --> 00:38:48,015
Insert it now.

807
00:38:48,153 --> 00:38:49,982
[pained shrieking]

808
00:38:50,120 --> 00:38:51,743
[shrieking stops]

809
00:38:51,881 --> 00:38:54,884
[shuddering breaths]

810
00:39:04,134 --> 00:39:05,550
There's more.

811
00:39:05,688 --> 00:39:08,691
79 years more.

812
00:39:10,762 --> 00:39:12,453
I have all of it.

813
00:39:12,591 --> 00:39:15,145
[whirring]

814
00:39:17,458 --> 00:39:19,460
[electronic trilling]

815
00:39:21,151 --> 00:39:23,361
[buzzing]

816
00:39:34,889 --> 00:39:38,099
Hugo is the only one who
had a relationship with it,

817
00:39:38,237 --> 00:39:40,619
and he knew what he
was doing with that thing.

818
00:39:40,757 --> 00:39:42,690
Pull up Kellner's data.

819
00:39:48,040 --> 00:39:49,421
Give me the device.

820
00:39:49,559 --> 00:39:51,043
BOYD:
If systolic goes below 90

821
00:39:51,181 --> 00:39:52,459
like last time,
I'm pulling you out.

822
00:39:52,597 --> 00:39:53,977
MED TECH:
Watch for tachyarrhythmia,

823
00:39:54,115 --> 00:39:55,738
- subdural hemorrhage.
- MED TECH 2: Copy.

824
00:39:55,876 --> 00:39:58,188
[monitor beeping]

825
00:39:59,604 --> 00:40:01,468
[quiet chatter]

826
00:40:01,606 --> 00:40:03,608
♪ ♪

827
00:40:11,478 --> 00:40:14,066
[beeping growing faster]

828
00:40:16,172 --> 00:40:17,311
[whimpers]

829
00:40:17,449 --> 00:40:20,072
[yells, groans]

830
00:40:20,210 --> 00:40:22,316
I'm fine. I'm fine!

831
00:40:22,454 --> 00:40:24,042
What happened?

832
00:40:26,354 --> 00:40:28,598
I had focus, gave myself over,

833
00:40:28,736 --> 00:40:31,463
saw Kellner for a split second,
then...

834
00:40:31,601 --> 00:40:33,051
sledgehammer, whiteout.

835
00:40:33,189 --> 00:40:35,640
Sucked all the air
out of my lungs.

836
00:40:35,778 --> 00:40:37,676
Is he an experiencer?

837
00:40:37,814 --> 00:40:39,437
You can't dive on them.

838
00:40:41,784 --> 00:40:44,096
He can't have been.
I'd have known.

839
00:40:44,234 --> 00:40:45,857
He's Hugo's guy.

840
00:40:45,995 --> 00:40:48,307
There's gonna be a whole
lot we don't know.

841
00:40:48,446 --> 00:40:51,000
Maybe, but I'm not going
back in there to find out.

842
00:41:01,251 --> 00:41:03,288
Pull the data on the girlfriend.

843
00:41:04,841 --> 00:41:08,500
There have been retrieval
programs of exotic craft.

844
00:41:09,605 --> 00:41:13,056
Interrogation of
nonhuman biologics.

845
00:41:13,194 --> 00:41:16,232
Reverse engineering and
technology exploitation.

846
00:41:16,370 --> 00:41:17,889
All of it...

847
00:41:18,027 --> 00:41:20,857
run by WARDEX,
the Department of Defense

848
00:41:20,995 --> 00:41:23,135
and the defense industry.

849
00:41:23,273 --> 00:41:25,655
It has the highest level
of military

850
00:41:25,793 --> 00:41:27,208
and private sector
classification

851
00:41:27,346 --> 00:41:28,693
in American history.

852
00:41:28,831 --> 00:41:30,073
[wind howling outside]

853
00:41:30,211 --> 00:41:31,489
They've run it
since the early '70s

854
00:41:31,627 --> 00:41:32,904
without government funding.

855
00:41:33,042 --> 00:41:35,009
Too many tax dollars
to try and hide,

856
00:41:35,147 --> 00:41:37,529
and-and off-world artifacts
are too profitable

857
00:41:37,667 --> 00:41:39,255
to leave in the hands
of appointed officials,

858
00:41:39,393 --> 00:41:42,120
especially after
the Nixon thing.

859
00:41:42,258 --> 00:41:45,882
Presidents are civilians again
after eight years, so...

860
00:41:46,020 --> 00:41:49,196
so there's no longer a reason
to read them in on any of this.

861
00:41:51,336 --> 00:41:54,512
I was a part of all that until
I saw what you just saw.

862
00:41:55,720 --> 00:41:59,102
This all stops now.

863
00:41:59,240 --> 00:42:00,828
What are you gonna do?

864
00:42:01,864 --> 00:42:06,420
Full disclosure to the
whole world all at once.

865
00:42:09,285 --> 00:42:12,115
Have you considered
what effect that'll have?

866
00:42:13,358 --> 00:42:15,015
On everything?

867
00:42:16,050 --> 00:42:17,431
What...

868
00:42:17,569 --> 00:42:19,260
It's not up to me
to decide if it's...

869
00:42:19,398 --> 00:42:22,229
if it's good or bad
for people to know.

870
00:42:22,367 --> 00:42:25,059
Then how is it up to you
to decide that the right to know

871
00:42:25,197 --> 00:42:27,475
outweighs the consequences
of knowing?

872
00:42:27,614 --> 00:42:29,374
Are you saying we leave
this up to WARDEX?

873
00:42:29,512 --> 00:42:31,894
'Cause they-they've already
decided this belongs to them,

874
00:42:32,032 --> 00:42:34,621
this core truth
about the universe.

875
00:42:34,759 --> 00:42:36,864
- It's wrong.
- You can't do that.

876
00:42:38,072 --> 00:42:39,695
Think about...

877
00:42:41,386 --> 00:42:42,801
People will see them as deities.

878
00:42:42,939 --> 00:42:44,838
- They'll stop believing in God.
- [scoffs]

879
00:42:44,976 --> 00:42:46,736
Well, you left the church.

880
00:42:46,874 --> 00:42:48,289
Not because I stopped believing,

881
00:42:48,427 --> 00:42:49,912
because I could no
longer say with certainty

882
00:42:50,050 --> 00:42:51,430
that God is divine,

883
00:42:51,569 --> 00:42:54,572
but I believe profoundly
that he's essential.

884
00:42:56,401 --> 00:42:57,885
He's how we define ourselves.

885
00:42:58,023 --> 00:43:00,854
He's what keeps whole
civilizations together.

886
00:43:02,476 --> 00:43:05,237
We've been raised to believe
in a supreme being,

887
00:43:05,375 --> 00:43:09,034
and now you want to show
us actual supreme beings?

888
00:43:09,172 --> 00:43:10,829
People can't handle both.

889
00:43:13,418 --> 00:43:15,075
Of course they can.

890
00:43:15,213 --> 00:43:16,732
No, they can't.

891
00:43:17,767 --> 00:43:19,700
Look at our history
with any sudden change.

892
00:43:20,770 --> 00:43:24,981
And now, with the world about
to blow up in all our faces?

893
00:43:26,638 --> 00:43:31,056
You'll get panic and-and chaos,
and God help us.

894
00:43:35,336 --> 00:43:37,442
Hugo's expecting me to check in.

895
00:43:49,247 --> 00:43:50,869
No signal.

896
00:43:52,699 --> 00:43:54,493
No signal.

897
00:43:54,632 --> 00:43:56,668
I'll try the other side
of the hill.

898
00:44:10,026 --> 00:44:12,304
[door opens and closes]

899
00:44:14,306 --> 00:44:16,377
[Jackson grunting, panting]

900
00:44:21,520 --> 00:44:23,557
[thunder rumbling]

901
00:44:26,767 --> 00:44:28,010
- Okay.
- [knocking]

902
00:44:28,148 --> 00:44:29,356
- Unlock the door!
- [engine starts]

903
00:44:29,494 --> 00:44:30,668
- What?
- Jackson, come on!

904
00:44:30,806 --> 00:44:32,462
- [lock clicks]
- Oh, shit. Sorry.

905
00:44:33,636 --> 00:44:35,327
Oh, sorry, sorry.

906
00:44:35,465 --> 00:44:37,847
- Okay.
- Oh, my God.

907
00:44:39,677 --> 00:44:42,058
[phone ringing]

908
00:44:42,196 --> 00:44:43,611
[Jackson stammers]

909
00:44:43,750 --> 00:44:45,234
If you answer that in French,
I swear to God

910
00:44:45,372 --> 00:44:46,614
I'm marching you
right back inside.

911
00:44:46,753 --> 00:44:48,306
Hello?

912
00:44:48,444 --> 00:44:50,273
HUGO [over phone]: 
I've been waiting a very long time

913
00:44:50,411 --> 00:44:52,551
to meet you, Ms. Fairchild.

914
00:44:52,690 --> 00:44:54,105
Who is this?

915
00:44:54,243 --> 00:44:55,865
A friend.

916
00:44:57,142 --> 00:44:59,835
And if I'm right about you,
Margaret,

917
00:44:59,973 --> 00:45:01,388
you'd know if I wasn't.

918
00:45:01,526 --> 00:45:02,907
No, I don't... I don't know you

919
00:45:03,045 --> 00:45:04,771
any more than I know
what's happening to me.

920
00:45:04,909 --> 00:45:07,083
HUGO: Very few people could
manage this as well as you.

921
00:45:07,221 --> 00:45:08,913
- I'm not managing it. I'm not.
- Who-who is that?

922
00:45:09,051 --> 00:45:11,363
I am frightened.
I'm frightened out of my wits.

923
00:45:11,501 --> 00:45:15,471
Because you're just a passenger
on your way somewhere.

924
00:45:15,609 --> 00:45:17,266
- Let us help you get there.
- Help me how?

925
00:45:17,404 --> 00:45:18,474
What do you mean?

926
00:45:18,612 --> 00:45:19,924
- Is that the FBI?
- Shh!

927
00:45:20,062 --> 00:45:21,097
HUGO: We want to offer you
our protection.

928
00:45:21,235 --> 00:45:22,616
We held back on reaching out

929
00:45:22,754 --> 00:45:24,652
until after we saw
your weather report.

930
00:45:24,791 --> 00:45:26,137
You held back?

931
00:45:26,275 --> 00:45:27,276
What do you mean?
What does that mean?

932
00:45:27,414 --> 00:45:29,174
Are you gonna need a lawyer?

933
00:45:32,937 --> 00:45:35,767
Who is 873-2626?

934
00:45:37,527 --> 00:45:38,874
Since you know that number,

935
00:45:39,012 --> 00:45:41,255
you must already know
who it belongs to.

936
00:45:43,602 --> 00:45:44,811
Kellner?

937
00:45:45,881 --> 00:45:46,778
Kellner?

938
00:45:46,916 --> 00:45:48,642
All right.

939
00:45:48,780 --> 00:45:50,299
Listen carefully.

940
00:45:50,437 --> 00:45:51,749
You cannot go home.

941
00:45:51,887 --> 00:45:53,164
If you have another
direction in mind,

942
00:45:53,302 --> 00:45:55,373
even a vague inclination,
follow it.

943
00:45:55,511 --> 00:45:57,202
If we can find you by phone,
others can

944
00:45:57,340 --> 00:45:59,066
- find you in the world.
- No, it's too late.

945
00:45:59,204 --> 00:46:00,585
They...
Uh, they already found me.

946
00:46:00,723 --> 00:46:03,312
Hang up immediately.
Destroy your phone.

947
00:46:03,450 --> 00:46:04,762
How will you find me?

948
00:46:04,900 --> 00:46:06,142
I have every confidence
you'll find us.

949
00:46:06,280 --> 00:46:07,281
Do it now.

950
00:46:09,111 --> 00:46:11,872
Wait, wait. What are you...
Wh-What are you doing?!

951
00:46:13,529 --> 00:46:14,461
Back up over the phone.

952
00:46:14,599 --> 00:46:16,359
- What?
- Back up!

953
00:46:16,497 --> 00:46:18,051
- Come on.
- Okay, I'd like to point out that I'm being

954
00:46:18,189 --> 00:46:20,329
extremely cool here
and that I'm rolling with it,

955
00:46:20,467 --> 00:46:22,469
and that was a $600 phone.

956
00:46:23,504 --> 00:46:25,403
Well, it's still a $600 phone
'cause you missed it.

957
00:46:25,541 --> 00:46:26,887
Jackson, pull forward
till you hear the crunch.

958
00:46:27,025 --> 00:46:28,026
- Come on.
- Sorry.

959
00:46:32,617 --> 00:46:34,688
Oh, my God, you missed it again.
Oh, my God.

960
00:46:34,826 --> 00:46:36,828
- Okay. [mutters]
- What?

961
00:46:40,625 --> 00:46:41,937
Okay.

962
00:46:43,628 --> 00:46:46,010
Pull forward. Go, go, go.

963
00:46:47,632 --> 00:46:49,392
Keep going. Keep going.

964
00:46:58,677 --> 00:47:00,990
Okay. Okay.

965
00:47:01,128 --> 00:47:04,338
- Okay, let's go. Let's go.
- Uh... wh-where?

966
00:47:04,476 --> 00:47:06,030
- North.
- Why?

967
00:47:06,168 --> 00:47:07,376
Because that's where
Daniel Kellner is.

968
00:47:07,514 --> 00:47:09,033
Oh, my God. [stammering]

969
00:47:09,171 --> 00:47:10,758
Who is this dude?
Is he some guy from your past

970
00:47:10,897 --> 00:47:12,312
- that you never told me about?
- I don't know, Jackson.

971
00:47:12,450 --> 00:47:13,658
- Or what is it?
- You're giving me a headache.

972
00:47:13,796 --> 00:47:14,521
I don't know what
I'm doing here.

973
00:47:14,659 --> 00:47:15,902
I don't know who he is.

974
00:47:16,040 --> 00:47:17,524
I just know he's someplace north.

975
00:47:17,662 --> 00:47:18,559
- That's all I know, okay?
- [hailstones clacking]

976
00:47:18,697 --> 00:47:20,009
Oh, my God. What is that sound?

977
00:47:22,494 --> 00:47:24,496
- Your hailstorm.
- Wow.

978
00:47:24,634 --> 00:47:25,946
Weather Shimmy?

979
00:47:26,084 --> 00:47:28,328
Just drive. Just drive.

980
00:47:38,027 --> 00:47:40,305
[electronic trilling, beeping]

981
00:47:40,443 --> 00:47:42,480
♪ ♪

982
00:48:08,195 --> 00:48:09,887
[sighs]

983
00:48:10,888 --> 00:48:12,268
[electronic warbling]

984
00:48:12,406 --> 00:48:14,339
[crate thuds on table]

985
00:48:16,859 --> 00:48:19,379
You got Kellner on 2626.

986
00:48:21,105 --> 00:48:22,692
Look at the video
I just sent you.

987
00:48:22,830 --> 00:48:24,142
DANIEL [over phone]:
Okay, hold on.

988
00:48:26,317 --> 00:48:28,319
[Margaret clicking tongue on video]

989
00:48:30,631 --> 00:48:32,081
Yeah. So?

990
00:48:32,219 --> 00:48:34,014
She's the one we've
been waiting for.

991
00:48:34,152 --> 00:48:36,499
DANIEL: Her? Why?

992
00:48:36,637 --> 00:48:38,881
Did you not hear her?

993
00:48:39,019 --> 00:48:40,400
DANIEL: Yeah, I heard her.

994
00:48:40,538 --> 00:48:41,815
And you still ask why?

995
00:48:41,953 --> 00:48:43,713
"Don't be afraid of
what you don't know"?

996
00:48:43,851 --> 00:48:45,612
That's all she had to say?

997
00:48:47,062 --> 00:48:49,064
"Don't be afraid of
what you don't know"?

998
00:48:49,202 --> 00:48:50,479
That's what she said?

999
00:48:50,617 --> 00:48:52,101
You didn't hear it?

1000
00:48:53,585 --> 00:48:55,104
We all heard it.

1001
00:48:55,242 --> 00:48:57,348
We couldn't understand it.
It's not English.

1002
00:48:57,486 --> 00:48:59,005
[chuckling]: Of course it is.

1003
00:48:59,143 --> 00:49:01,076
I'm listening to it right now.

1004
00:49:01,214 --> 00:49:03,009
I'm sending you to Kansas City,
where she's from.

1005
00:49:03,147 --> 00:49:05,011
- We'll get a car to you. Leave tonight.
- Hey, wait.

1006
00:49:05,149 --> 00:49:06,667
- Wait a second. Wait a second.
- Do not travel by day.

1007
00:49:06,805 --> 00:49:08,083
You're not hearing it?
It's-it's perfectly clear.

1008
00:49:08,221 --> 00:49:09,187
Detour past tollbooths
and turnpikes.

1009
00:49:09,325 --> 00:49:10,533
DANIEL: Hey, listen to me.

1010
00:49:10,671 --> 00:49:11,741
Have you played this
to other people?

1011
00:49:11,879 --> 00:49:13,847
Stay with me.

1012
00:49:13,985 --> 00:49:16,608
A motel room key will be
in the car with directions.

1013
00:49:16,746 --> 00:49:18,541
Santiago will retrieve you
in the morning.

1014
00:49:18,679 --> 00:49:21,061
By then, I'll know
what comes next.

1015
00:49:21,199 --> 00:49:23,788
Hugo, you're scaring
the shit out of me.

1016
00:49:23,926 --> 00:49:27,550
There are two of you, Daniel.

1017
00:49:27,688 --> 00:49:30,795
There's always been
just the two of you.

1018
00:49:30,933 --> 00:49:32,797
[rustling]

1019
00:49:32,935 --> 00:49:34,972
♪ ♪

1020
00:49:59,134 --> 00:50:00,859
[breathing heavily]

1021
00:50:02,378 --> 00:50:04,415
[pills rattling]

1022
00:50:10,179 --> 00:50:12,733
[gasping]

1023
00:50:12,871 --> 00:50:15,150
[trembling breaths]

1024
00:50:20,120 --> 00:50:21,466
[exhales slowly]

1025
00:50:24,228 --> 00:50:26,230
[trembling breaths continue]

1026
00:50:27,817 --> 00:50:29,543
[whirring]

1027
00:50:40,244 --> 00:50:42,729
♪ ♪

1028
00:50:43,833 --> 00:50:46,146
[muffled shattering]

1029
00:50:55,604 --> 00:50:58,227
[glass shards clinking]

1030
00:51:17,764 --> 00:51:19,800
♪ ♪

1031
00:51:29,672 --> 00:51:31,502
- [hands clap]
- [gasps]

1032
00:51:31,640 --> 00:51:33,676
[sharp, heavy breathing]

1033
00:51:39,786 --> 00:51:41,891
[praying in Latin]

1034
00:51:59,633 --> 00:52:01,670
♪ ♪

1035
00:52:26,143 --> 00:52:27,661
Hello, Jane.

1036
00:52:27,799 --> 00:52:29,560
Please.

1037
00:52:30,940 --> 00:52:32,977
Have a seat.

1038
00:52:38,638 --> 00:52:41,192
Where are you right now, Jane?

1039
00:52:41,330 --> 00:52:43,021
What is your location?

1040
00:52:44,299 --> 00:52:46,611
- I don't know.
- Relax, please.

1041
00:52:50,028 --> 00:52:52,514
- Who are you?
- I'll ask the questions.

1042
00:52:53,618 --> 00:52:55,344
Are you still with
Daniel Kellner?

1043
00:53:01,557 --> 00:53:02,869
He's outside.

1044
00:53:06,528 --> 00:53:08,115
Where were you last night?

1045
00:53:09,910 --> 00:53:11,947
[breath trembling]

1046
00:53:14,156 --> 00:53:15,502
[snarls]

1047
00:53:15,640 --> 00:53:17,573
[panting]

1048
00:53:17,711 --> 00:53:20,369
- BP's high but holding: 156/94.
- O2's decent at 96,

1049
00:53:20,507 --> 00:53:22,337
- but sodium's climbing.
- Heart rate's hot, too-- 118.

1050
00:53:22,475 --> 00:53:23,545
- Potassium's borderline, too.
- Jane!

1051
00:53:23,683 --> 00:53:25,202
- Stand by, Ringer's.
- Jane!

1052
00:53:26,168 --> 00:53:27,687
- Jane!
- [gasps]

1053
00:53:27,825 --> 00:53:30,068
Where were you last night?

1054
00:53:31,277 --> 00:53:34,211
Monastery of St. Clare
of the Dawn.

1055
00:53:34,349 --> 00:53:36,454
Monastery St. Clare?

1056
00:53:36,592 --> 00:53:38,007
Of course.

1057
00:53:38,145 --> 00:53:41,114
I remember St. Clare
from my Sunday school.

1058
00:53:41,252 --> 00:53:43,150
She was too sick to go
to midnight Mass,

1059
00:53:43,289 --> 00:53:45,877
and she had a vision
of it instead.

1060
00:53:46,015 --> 00:53:48,501
She was in two places at once,
like me.

1061
00:53:51,228 --> 00:53:53,264
Monastery of St. Clare. Got it.

1062
00:53:53,402 --> 00:53:55,301
13 miles southeast
of the District.

1063
00:53:55,439 --> 00:53:57,889
When you left,
which way did you drive?

1064
00:53:59,063 --> 00:54:01,479
[Jane's breath trembling]

1065
00:54:01,617 --> 00:54:02,825
I don't know.

1066
00:54:02,963 --> 00:54:04,482
Was the sun up?

1067
00:54:07,623 --> 00:54:09,004
Yes.

1068
00:54:09,142 --> 00:54:11,282
Did you drive into it
or away from it?

1069
00:54:14,768 --> 00:54:16,391
It was on the right.

1070
00:54:18,565 --> 00:54:19,980
I don't like you.

1071
00:54:20,118 --> 00:54:21,879
Not required.

1072
00:54:22,017 --> 00:54:23,467
Sun on the right.

1073
00:54:23,605 --> 00:54:25,227
Sun on the right--
they're headed due north,

1074
00:54:25,365 --> 00:54:26,642
possibly northwest.

1075
00:54:26,780 --> 00:54:28,403
Could be on 27, 18
or the interstate.

1076
00:54:28,541 --> 00:54:29,956
Interstate not likely.

1077
00:54:30,094 --> 00:54:31,613
Focus on frontage roads
or county highways.

1078
00:54:31,751 --> 00:54:34,271
Did you pass a street sign?

1079
00:54:34,409 --> 00:54:35,824
JANE: Yes.

1080
00:54:35,962 --> 00:54:37,688
What did it say?

1081
00:54:37,826 --> 00:54:39,828
[breath continues trembling]

1082
00:54:42,037 --> 00:54:45,178
"Silver Spring: 120 miles."

1083
00:54:45,316 --> 00:54:47,698
Street sign,
"Silver Spring: 120 miles."

1084
00:54:47,836 --> 00:54:50,459
AGENT: I've got half a dozen
towns off the 26.

1085
00:54:50,597 --> 00:54:53,773
Silver Hollow, Oakshade,
Ironmere, Stonemont...

1086
00:54:53,911 --> 00:54:55,706
Try for more details, Jane.

1087
00:54:55,844 --> 00:54:57,363
What else did you pass?

1088
00:54:57,501 --> 00:54:59,123
[breath continues trembling]

1089
00:54:59,261 --> 00:55:00,331
A river.

1090
00:55:00,469 --> 00:55:02,057
Passed a river.

1091
00:55:02,195 --> 00:55:04,231
Did you see a sign
for a town after that?

1092
00:55:06,475 --> 00:55:08,546
- Yes.
- What did it say?

1093
00:55:10,099 --> 00:55:12,964
[whimpering]

1094
00:55:13,102 --> 00:55:14,690
S-Sykesville.

1095
00:55:14,828 --> 00:55:17,486
- Sykesville.
- Sykesville.

1096
00:55:18,729 --> 00:55:21,179
Field is narrowed.
Track and converge.

1097
00:55:21,318 --> 00:55:23,975
Charlie 27, take the lead.
You're four miles out.

1098
00:55:24,113 --> 00:55:26,392
Maintain maximum legal speed.

1099
00:55:26,530 --> 00:55:29,291
How soon after you saw
the sign did you make a turn?

1100
00:55:29,429 --> 00:55:31,017
- A few minutes.
- Few minutes.

1101
00:55:31,155 --> 00:55:33,053
Did you turn right or left?

1102
00:55:33,191 --> 00:55:34,676
- Right.
- Right.

1103
00:55:34,814 --> 00:55:37,403
Do you remember
the name of the road?

1104
00:55:37,541 --> 00:55:38,783
No.

1105
00:55:38,921 --> 00:55:40,820
Do you remember anything
about the road?

1106
00:55:42,097 --> 00:55:43,201
[breath continues trembling]

1107
00:55:43,340 --> 00:55:45,583
[whirring]

1108
00:55:47,551 --> 00:55:49,346
[breath stops trembling]

1109
00:55:49,484 --> 00:55:51,209
It was a dirt road.

1110
00:55:51,348 --> 00:55:52,763
Dirt road.

1111
00:55:52,901 --> 00:55:54,558
Ash Hollow Road,
three and a quarter miles

1112
00:55:54,696 --> 00:55:56,905
outside Sykesville, dead end.

1113
00:55:57,043 --> 00:55:58,493
Farmhouse at the end.

1114
00:55:58,631 --> 00:55:59,908
And found it.

1115
00:56:00,046 --> 00:56:01,358
Ash Hollow Road.

1116
00:56:01,496 --> 00:56:03,670
Target is a farmhouse.

1117
00:56:04,706 --> 00:56:06,915
[tires squealing]

1118
00:56:10,574 --> 00:56:12,817
You've done very well, Jane.

1119
00:56:12,955 --> 00:56:15,475
A service to your country.

1120
00:56:15,613 --> 00:56:18,892
But I have to ask you
one more thing.

1121
00:56:19,030 --> 00:56:23,069
If we can't find Daniel
or we miss him again,

1122
00:56:23,207 --> 00:56:25,589
you may need to
stop him yourself

1123
00:56:25,727 --> 00:56:27,591
any way you can.

1124
00:56:29,869 --> 00:56:32,423
[cries out in pain]

1125
00:56:34,218 --> 00:56:36,151
Hang on. BP just tanked.
88 on 62.

1126
00:56:36,289 --> 00:56:38,118
Uh, heart rate's dropping--
down to 59.

1127
00:56:38,256 --> 00:56:41,121
- Uh, O2 is 93 and falling. 91.
- [Scanlon coughing]

1128
00:56:41,259 --> 00:56:44,055
[breathing deeply]

1129
00:56:45,781 --> 00:56:47,749
92 on 60 and holding.
O2's still dropping, though.

1130
00:56:47,887 --> 00:56:48,819
- Let's start bagging.
- [monitor beeping rapidly]

1131
00:56:48,957 --> 00:56:50,268
Make sure you secure the airway.

1132
00:56:50,407 --> 00:56:52,926
- [air pumping]
- High 80s. Keep going.

1133
00:56:53,064 --> 00:56:54,997
Get away!

1134
00:56:55,135 --> 00:56:57,137
- [breathing heavily]
- [beeping slows]

1135
00:57:00,382 --> 00:57:02,177
Jane.

1136
00:57:03,247 --> 00:57:06,284
What Daniel is
trying to do is wrong.

1137
00:57:06,423 --> 00:57:08,873
It's dangerous.

1138
00:57:09,011 --> 00:57:12,290
It would tip the balance in
an already destabilized world.

1139
00:57:13,291 --> 00:57:14,534
JANE: Yes.

1140
00:57:14,672 --> 00:57:16,743
Jane, could you stop him
if you had to?

1141
00:57:16,881 --> 00:57:19,643
No. No.

1142
00:57:22,680 --> 00:57:25,580
"Father, if you be willing,

1143
00:57:25,718 --> 00:57:28,652
"let this cup pass me by.

1144
00:57:28,790 --> 00:57:32,034
Yet not as I will,
but as you will."

1145
00:57:32,172 --> 00:57:34,485
And what did Christ say next?

1146
00:57:36,245 --> 00:57:38,558
"By my will,
thine will be done."

1147
00:57:39,628 --> 00:57:43,114
If the moment comes,
I'll be with you,

1148
00:57:43,252 --> 00:57:45,151
and you'll act, Jane,

1149
00:57:45,289 --> 00:57:48,844
out of love for Daniel,
out of love for the human race.

1150
00:57:52,192 --> 00:57:53,849
Now look around the room.

1151
00:57:55,023 --> 00:57:56,438
Slowly.

1152
00:57:59,959 --> 00:58:01,132
Left to right.

1153
00:58:04,411 --> 00:58:05,827
Stop there.

1154
00:58:07,242 --> 00:58:08,692
Get up.

1155
00:58:12,558 --> 00:58:13,697
Walk to the counter.

1156
00:58:13,835 --> 00:58:15,837
♪ ♪

1157
00:58:21,739 --> 00:58:23,569
Pull out the chopping knife.

1158
00:58:30,783 --> 00:58:31,991
Give me your phone!

1159
00:58:32,129 --> 00:58:33,786
- Oh, shit! What?
- Give me your phone.

1160
00:58:33,924 --> 00:58:35,270
Jackson, come on, come on,
come on, give me your phone.

1161
00:58:35,408 --> 00:58:36,547
Give me your phone.
Give me your phone.

1162
00:58:36,685 --> 00:58:38,100
- Okay, hold on, hold on!
- Come on!

1163
00:58:38,238 --> 00:58:38,860
Why? So you can throw it
out the window again?

1164
00:58:38,998 --> 00:58:41,276
[phone ringing]

1165
00:58:41,414 --> 00:58:43,105
Hey, Hugo, why am I
the only one...

1166
00:58:43,243 --> 00:58:45,798
- Daniel Kellner.
- Oh, my God, Daniel Kellner.

1167
00:58:45,936 --> 00:58:47,385
MARGARET [over phone]:
They know where you are.

1168
00:58:47,524 --> 00:58:48,801
They know. Do you understand?

1169
00:58:48,939 --> 00:58:49,905
Who is this?

1170
00:58:50,043 --> 00:58:51,597
Do not go back to the house.

1171
00:58:51,735 --> 00:58:53,978
Scan-Scanlon dove on Jane.

1172
00:58:54,116 --> 00:58:55,601
Does that mean anything to you?

1173
00:58:55,739 --> 00:58:57,430
- Okay. Give me your...
- Look, they found you.

1174
00:58:57,568 --> 00:58:59,225
I don't know who you are,
and I don't know who they are,

1175
00:58:59,363 --> 00:59:00,951
but they're gonna kill you.

1176
00:59:01,089 --> 00:59:02,435
- Give me the phone.
- They are gonna kill you both.

1177
00:59:02,573 --> 00:59:04,264
- Give me my phone!
- You need to leave.

1178
00:59:04,402 --> 00:59:05,611
Give me my phone, Maggie!
Give me my phone! Oh, my God!

1179
00:59:05,749 --> 00:59:07,371
I'm so done with your crazy shit!

1180
00:59:07,509 --> 00:59:09,028
[line clicks]

1181
00:59:14,551 --> 00:59:16,553
[panting]

1182
00:59:19,417 --> 00:59:21,454
[vehicles approaching]

1183
00:59:31,706 --> 00:59:33,708
[Daniel breathing heavily]

1184
00:59:41,750 --> 00:59:43,580
[softly]: Okay. Okay.

1185
00:59:51,277 --> 00:59:54,142
[birds chirping]

1186
01:00:01,183 --> 01:00:03,220
[panting]

1187
01:00:21,859 --> 01:00:23,447
[vehicle door opens]

1188
01:00:23,585 --> 01:00:25,138
[grunts]

1189
01:00:26,623 --> 01:00:28,452
[vehicle door closes]

1190
01:00:44,123 --> 01:00:46,125
[indistinct chatter]

1191
01:00:48,368 --> 01:00:49,956
[car door opens]

1192
01:00:58,447 --> 01:00:59,897
Okay.

1193
01:01:02,003 --> 01:01:03,487
[engine starts]

1194
01:01:03,625 --> 01:01:05,247
What am I doing?
What am I doing?

1195
01:01:05,385 --> 01:01:07,629
What am I doing?
What am I doing? Okay.

1196
01:01:07,767 --> 01:01:09,389
What am I doing?
What am I doing?

1197
01:01:09,527 --> 01:01:11,253
- What am I doing? What am I doing?
- Hold it!

1198
01:01:11,391 --> 01:01:13,221
- What am I doing? What am I doing? What am I doing?
- Stop!

1199
01:01:13,359 --> 01:01:14,636
- Hey! He's in the car!
- Watch out, watch out, watch out!

1200
01:01:14,774 --> 01:01:16,500
- What am I doing?
- [engine revving]

1201
01:01:16,638 --> 01:01:18,329
AGENT: Shoot the tires!

1202
01:01:18,467 --> 01:01:19,676
It's him! It's him!

1203
01:01:19,814 --> 01:01:21,125
Watch out!

1204
01:01:21,263 --> 01:01:23,024
[indistinct shouting]

1205
01:01:23,162 --> 01:01:25,578
[gunfire]

1206
01:01:26,683 --> 01:01:28,236
AGENT: Go for the tires!

1207
01:01:30,203 --> 01:01:32,896
[panting]

1208
01:01:34,483 --> 01:01:36,037
Oh, shit.

1209
01:01:37,141 --> 01:01:39,419
[engines revving in distance]

1210
01:01:47,496 --> 01:01:49,636
[tires squealing]

1211
01:01:53,295 --> 01:01:54,814
What am I doing?
What am I doing?

1212
01:01:54,952 --> 01:01:57,092
What am I doing?
What am I doing? What am I...

1213
01:01:57,230 --> 01:01:58,922
What am I doing?

1214
01:02:03,236 --> 01:02:04,375
- Hands up!
- Stop!

1215
01:02:04,513 --> 01:02:05,583
Get him!

1216
01:02:05,722 --> 01:02:07,068
Get out! Now!

1217
01:02:07,206 --> 01:02:08,138
- Get out of the car!
- [engine revving]

1218
01:02:08,276 --> 01:02:09,484
Let me see your hands!
Hands up!

1219
01:02:09,622 --> 01:02:11,244
- Hands up!
- [tires squealing]

1220
01:02:23,912 --> 01:02:25,914
♪ ♪

1221
01:02:27,916 --> 01:02:29,918
[breathing heavily]

1222
01:02:41,619 --> 01:02:43,863
[engines revving]

1223
01:02:44,761 --> 01:02:46,383
[Daniel grunts]

1224
01:02:47,798 --> 01:02:49,282
Get your seat belt on!

1225
01:03:00,017 --> 01:03:01,018
Jane!

1226
01:03:02,123 --> 01:03:03,365
Jane.

1227
01:03:04,746 --> 01:03:06,265
[engines revving]

1228
01:03:13,928 --> 01:03:16,620
[breathing heavily]

1229
01:03:18,967 --> 01:03:20,003
[whimpering]

1230
01:03:20,141 --> 01:03:21,487
[heavy, shaky breathing]

1231
01:03:21,625 --> 01:03:23,040
[straining]

1232
01:03:23,178 --> 01:03:24,076
[grunts]

1233
01:03:24,214 --> 01:03:26,457
[whimpering, straining]

1234
01:03:28,528 --> 01:03:30,703
- [screams]
- [cries out in pain]

1235
01:03:30,841 --> 01:03:32,843
[breathing heavily]

1236
01:03:32,981 --> 01:03:35,259
[indistinct chatter]

1237
01:03:35,397 --> 01:03:37,227
- He's seizing. Stretch him out.
- Watch his head.

1238
01:03:37,365 --> 01:03:38,469
- Watch his head.
- I need a bite block.

1239
01:03:38,607 --> 01:03:40,644
♪ ♪

1240
01:03:45,338 --> 01:03:46,512
[grunts]

1241
01:03:50,378 --> 01:03:51,655
[gun fires]

1242
01:03:51,793 --> 01:03:52,863
Get down!

1243
01:03:57,903 --> 01:03:59,766
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!

1244
01:03:59,905 --> 01:04:01,216
[tires squealing]

1245
01:04:01,354 --> 01:04:02,390
[gasps]

1246
01:04:07,878 --> 01:04:10,363
No, no, no, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

1247
01:04:10,501 --> 01:04:11,882
No, no, no, no, no.

1248
01:04:12,020 --> 01:04:13,815
Look, Jane, it wasn't you.
It wasn't you.

1249
01:04:13,953 --> 01:04:15,196
It was Scanlon.

1250
01:04:15,334 --> 01:04:16,680
The device. The device.

1251
01:04:16,818 --> 01:04:18,993
Roll him on three.
One, two, three, go.

1252
01:04:24,584 --> 01:04:26,207
What the hell just happened?

1253
01:04:31,971 --> 01:04:33,214
- Secure the device!
- I got it. I got it.

1254
01:04:33,352 --> 01:04:34,456
I'm gloved. I'm gloved.

1255
01:04:41,705 --> 01:04:43,672
[tires squeal]

1256
01:04:47,642 --> 01:04:49,886
[engine revving]

1257
01:04:52,233 --> 01:04:54,166
Look behind us!
Tell me what you see!

1258
01:05:00,586 --> 01:05:03,209
Dust. I see dust.

1259
01:05:04,762 --> 01:05:06,937
They're coming! They're coming!

1260
01:05:08,076 --> 01:05:09,940
Stop, stop, stop, stop!

1261
01:05:10,078 --> 01:05:11,977
[tires squealing]

1262
01:05:12,115 --> 01:05:14,289
[rocks clattering]

1263
01:05:18,915 --> 01:05:20,813
[panting]

1264
01:05:31,720 --> 01:05:33,067
Run!

1265
01:05:34,102 --> 01:05:35,483
JANE: Wait!

1266
01:05:37,105 --> 01:05:39,452
- What are you doing?
- Put it in drive!

1267
01:05:59,576 --> 01:06:01,647
[urgent chatter]

1268
01:06:01,785 --> 01:06:03,580
- You see them?
- You got a visual?

1269
01:06:03,718 --> 01:06:05,168
- Anybody got eyes on anything?
- They must have gone over.

1270
01:06:05,306 --> 01:06:06,859
Requesting underwater
search and recovery

1271
01:06:06,997 --> 01:06:08,240
- on site right now.
- They're down. They're down.

1272
01:06:08,378 --> 01:06:10,104
They're down.
They're in the water.

1273
01:06:10,242 --> 01:06:11,484
Can we get a team down there
and see if we can find them?

1274
01:06:11,622 --> 01:06:12,830
- We need some divers.
- Down there.

1275
01:06:12,969 --> 01:06:15,109
[chatter continues indistinctly]

1276
01:06:15,247 --> 01:06:17,214
[horns honking]

1277
01:06:17,352 --> 01:06:19,354
[panicked chatter]

1278
01:06:36,199 --> 01:06:37,786
They all think the
world's going to hell.

1279
01:06:37,924 --> 01:06:39,374
Got to get going now,
Jackson, okay?

1280
01:06:39,512 --> 01:06:40,755
Daniel Kellner's gonna be there.

1281
01:06:40,893 --> 01:06:42,412
Not right now,
but he will be soon.

1282
01:06:42,550 --> 01:06:44,069
- We got to go north.
- No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

1283
01:06:44,207 --> 01:06:46,036
- Got to go north right now.
- No, we need to...

1284
01:06:46,174 --> 01:06:47,831
- We need to go back to the hospital.
- No, no, no, Jack.

1285
01:06:47,969 --> 01:06:48,866
This is not something you
get treated for. It's not...

1286
01:06:49,005 --> 01:06:50,592
You know what's wrong with you,

1287
01:06:50,730 --> 01:06:52,146
is that you think there's
something wrong with me.

1288
01:06:52,284 --> 01:06:54,113
Look at me. Look at me.

1289
01:06:56,046 --> 01:06:57,875
If I moved, you'd stay.

1290
01:06:59,049 --> 01:07:00,430
- What?
- Kansas City.

1291
01:07:00,568 --> 01:07:02,604
You want me to move.
You're gonna stay.

1292
01:07:22,797 --> 01:07:24,281
[sighs]

1293
01:07:24,419 --> 01:07:27,112
You know, this thing
that's happening, it's...

1294
01:07:27,250 --> 01:07:28,941
[takes deep breath]

1295
01:07:29,079 --> 01:07:30,391
It's not coming from me.

1296
01:07:30,529 --> 01:07:33,049
It's like I'm just a passenger.

1297
01:07:33,187 --> 01:07:34,567
That's not a bad thing.

1298
01:07:34,705 --> 01:07:36,983
It's, like, a really good thing.

1299
01:07:38,054 --> 01:07:39,952
- It's like your music.
- Uh-huh.

1300
01:07:40,090 --> 01:07:42,299
You know when you're
in the flow?

1301
01:07:42,437 --> 01:07:44,474
And it just feels...

1302
01:07:46,441 --> 01:07:48,133
I'm in the flow.

1303
01:07:48,271 --> 01:07:49,306
Okay.

1304
01:07:49,444 --> 01:07:50,790
And I told you I'd tell you

1305
01:07:50,928 --> 01:07:54,139
when I get where
I'm supposed to be, and...

1306
01:07:54,277 --> 01:07:55,864
this is it.

1307
01:07:56,002 --> 01:07:57,935
- Okay.
- Right here.

1308
01:07:58,074 --> 01:08:00,731
- It's where I'm supposed to be.
- Okay.

1309
01:08:00,869 --> 01:08:03,700
S-So...

1310
01:08:03,838 --> 01:08:08,670
we need to go north because
that's where Daniel Kellner is?

1311
01:08:08,808 --> 01:08:10,776
Sorry. No. He's east.

1312
01:08:10,914 --> 01:08:12,364
- Oh. And...
- He's east now.

1313
01:08:12,502 --> 01:08:14,124
How do you know that it's east?

1314
01:08:14,262 --> 01:08:17,438
It's just, I have this
vague inclination.

1315
01:08:17,576 --> 01:08:19,129
But he's east now.
He's somewhere east.

1316
01:08:19,267 --> 01:08:21,890
And where is "somewhere"?

1317
01:08:23,789 --> 01:08:25,549
You want me to drive?

1318
01:08:27,241 --> 01:08:28,828
I need a water.

1319
01:08:35,904 --> 01:08:37,320
[entry bell jingling]

1320
01:08:42,497 --> 01:08:43,774
Hey.

1321
01:08:43,912 --> 01:08:45,707
Hello. Hi.

1322
01:08:46,674 --> 01:08:48,779
Hi. Um...

1323
01:08:51,092 --> 01:08:52,576
Will you do me a favor?

1324
01:08:52,714 --> 01:08:54,475
- Dr. Coleman?
- [lively chatter]

1325
01:08:54,613 --> 01:08:56,580
Uh, uh, yes, yes. Thank you,
thank you for taking the call.

1326
01:08:56,718 --> 01:08:58,548
Uh, I-I don't know.

1327
01:08:58,686 --> 01:09:02,414
She just took off, and y-y-yes,
it's getting worse, much worse.

1328
01:09:02,552 --> 01:09:03,794
Yes, please. Thank you.

1329
01:09:03,932 --> 01:09:05,037
Yes. Hold on one second.

1330
01:09:05,175 --> 01:09:06,452
Excuse me, sir.

1331
01:09:06,590 --> 01:09:07,936
Do you know the address
around here?

1332
01:09:08,074 --> 01:09:10,146
37 Pearl Street, Decatur.

1333
01:09:11,147 --> 01:09:14,184
37 Pearl Street, Decatur.

1334
01:09:14,322 --> 01:09:16,048
We'll be here. Thank you.

1335
01:09:16,186 --> 01:09:17,636
[entry bell jingling]

1336
01:09:26,955 --> 01:09:28,681
BOY: Hey, mister.

1337
01:09:29,717 --> 01:09:33,376
She said to say she loves you,
but she's going east.

1338
01:09:49,530 --> 01:09:51,048
Why Kansas City?

1339
01:09:51,187 --> 01:09:54,224
Best to focus on getting
you there tomorrow.

1340
01:09:54,362 --> 01:09:56,744
DANIEL [panting]:
Hugo, I'm...

1341
01:09:58,573 --> 01:10:00,196
Uh, it's coming back to me.

1342
01:10:00,334 --> 01:10:02,094
Things are coming back to me.

1343
01:10:02,232 --> 01:10:03,509
What things?

1344
01:10:03,647 --> 01:10:05,373
Animals.

1345
01:10:05,511 --> 01:10:08,687
Friendly, terrifying animals
looking at me.

1346
01:10:10,447 --> 01:10:13,416
And you can't look away
no matter how hard you try?

1347
01:10:13,554 --> 01:10:16,108
No, no.
They have to look away first.

1348
01:10:18,938 --> 01:10:21,527
Is this a memory or a dream?

1349
01:10:22,563 --> 01:10:24,185
I can't tell anymore.

1350
01:10:24,323 --> 01:10:26,498
[shower water running]

1351
01:10:28,534 --> 01:10:30,122
HUGO: Daniel?

1352
01:10:32,228 --> 01:10:33,677
Daniel.

1353
01:10:34,713 --> 01:10:36,162
Daniel.

1354
01:10:36,301 --> 01:10:38,441
It wasn't your idea
to recruit me, was it?

1355
01:10:38,579 --> 01:10:41,823
Not just for this but-but to
WARDEX in the first place.

1356
01:10:44,550 --> 01:10:46,069
No, it wasn't.

1357
01:10:46,207 --> 01:10:48,589
And there was a reason?

1358
01:10:48,727 --> 01:10:50,901
A specific reason
why you wanted me?

1359
01:10:52,558 --> 01:10:55,837
Other than your prodigious
gift for numbers? Yes.

1360
01:10:56,942 --> 01:10:59,703
You decided to keep
all of this to yourself?

1361
01:10:59,841 --> 01:11:02,844
Because I care about you.

1362
01:11:02,982 --> 01:11:04,777
Because you have a job to do.

1363
01:11:04,915 --> 01:11:08,402
And nothing can get
in the way of that.

1364
01:11:11,197 --> 01:11:13,234
There's parts of me...

1365
01:11:15,271 --> 01:11:18,412
...from when I was a kid
that I should be able to know,

1366
01:11:18,550 --> 01:11:20,172
and I don't.

1367
01:11:23,762 --> 01:11:25,281
They're just gone.

1368
01:11:26,282 --> 01:11:28,284
I'm so scared.

1369
01:11:29,630 --> 01:11:31,597
You don't need to be.

1370
01:11:31,735 --> 01:11:34,497
You have me and someone else.

1371
01:11:34,635 --> 01:11:38,432
And when the time is right,
everything will become clear.

1372
01:11:38,570 --> 01:11:41,124
Daniel, there's a place
you'll need to be

1373
01:11:41,262 --> 01:11:43,229
in the morning without fail.

1374
01:11:43,368 --> 01:11:46,060
There will be no other
day like tomorrow.

1375
01:11:48,994 --> 01:11:51,341
Where do you need me to go?

1376
01:11:53,654 --> 01:11:55,656
KCXE?

1377
01:11:55,794 --> 01:11:57,520
What's KCXE?

1378
01:12:38,388 --> 01:12:40,425
Danny, I'm gonna ask you
to do something.

1379
01:12:40,563 --> 01:12:42,219
[Margaret speaking indistinctly on video]

1380
01:12:42,358 --> 01:12:44,290
I want you first to look at this.

1381
01:12:45,361 --> 01:12:47,570
[Margaret speaking unintelligibly on video]

1382
01:12:48,881 --> 01:12:50,504
Do you understand what
she's saying?

1383
01:12:51,746 --> 01:12:53,541
I hear her. It-it's gibberish.

1384
01:12:53,679 --> 01:12:55,232
I can't understand it.

1385
01:12:55,371 --> 01:12:59,029
Okay, I-I just heard this
for the first time,

1386
01:12:59,167 --> 01:13:00,445
and I can.

1387
01:13:00,583 --> 01:13:02,136
- It's English.
- English?

1388
01:13:02,274 --> 01:13:04,276
I mean, it's-it's math
turned English in my head,

1389
01:13:04,414 --> 01:13:06,002
translated into words.

1390
01:13:07,037 --> 01:13:10,351
When I look at this,
I hear this.

1391
01:13:10,489 --> 01:13:13,389
[Margaret clicking tongue on video]

1392
01:13:14,907 --> 01:13:17,220
Danny, I'm gonna ask you
to do something.

1393
01:13:26,263 --> 01:13:27,920
You can't trust me anymore.

1394
01:13:31,372 --> 01:13:33,374
- [insects chirping]
- [sign creaking]

1395
01:13:46,974 --> 01:13:48,320
[gasps softly]

1396
01:13:49,942 --> 01:13:51,288
[hisses in pain]

1397
01:13:51,427 --> 01:13:53,636
[sighs]

1398
01:13:53,774 --> 01:13:55,603
[whimpers]

1399
01:14:01,816 --> 01:14:03,818
♪ ♪

1400
01:14:23,597 --> 01:14:25,599
♪ ♪

1401
01:14:40,303 --> 01:14:42,167
- [breathing heavily]
- [monitor beeping steadily]

1402
01:14:42,305 --> 01:14:44,031
Got him.

1403
01:14:46,343 --> 01:14:48,311
[groans]

1404
01:14:52,833 --> 01:14:54,835
[engine revving]

1405
01:15:12,335 --> 01:15:14,682
[engines revving]

1406
01:15:23,070 --> 01:15:24,865
[tires squealing]

1407
01:15:26,142 --> 01:15:28,178
[Daniel gasping]

1408
01:15:30,629 --> 01:15:33,045
[urgent chatter]

1409
01:15:35,738 --> 01:15:37,187
- They're here.
- [gasps]

1410
01:15:37,325 --> 01:15:38,568
- They're here.
- What?

1411
01:15:38,706 --> 01:15:40,881
- Take that end.
- Go, go, go.

1412
01:15:41,019 --> 01:15:42,917
[panting]

1413
01:15:44,401 --> 01:15:47,025
- The backpack. The backpack!
- You first.

1414
01:15:50,511 --> 01:15:52,548
[urgent chatter continues]

1415
01:15:59,589 --> 01:16:00,659
Come on.

1416
01:16:00,797 --> 01:16:03,075
This is all I've got.

1417
01:16:03,213 --> 01:16:04,560
You're coming, right?

1418
01:16:04,698 --> 01:16:05,975
- [banging at door]
- Shit.

1419
01:16:06,113 --> 01:16:07,252
Breach! Here!

1420
01:16:08,218 --> 01:16:09,841
[urgent chatter]

1421
01:16:09,979 --> 01:16:11,118
- No, come on, come on, come on.
- You got to take this.

1422
01:16:11,256 --> 01:16:12,913
[urgent chatter continues]

1423
01:16:13,051 --> 01:16:16,054
And for God's sake, Jane,
don't touch what's inside.

1424
01:16:16,192 --> 01:16:17,158
Go. Go.

1425
01:16:17,296 --> 01:16:19,298
[urgent chatter continues]

1426
01:16:23,233 --> 01:16:25,581
- [grunting]
- Get out of there!

1427
01:16:32,139 --> 01:16:33,761
Get on the ground!

1428
01:16:36,626 --> 01:16:38,214
They're burned.

1429
01:16:41,044 --> 01:16:42,632
[breathing heavily]

1430
01:16:42,770 --> 01:16:44,738
[agents shouting indistinctly in distance]

1431
01:16:54,471 --> 01:16:56,094
It's not here.

1432
01:17:00,995 --> 01:17:02,479
Where's the device?

1433
01:17:07,692 --> 01:17:09,210
[sighs]

1434
01:17:09,348 --> 01:17:11,350
[jet engine whirring]

1435
01:17:19,186 --> 01:17:21,222
♪ ♪

1436
01:17:43,728 --> 01:17:45,074
SCANLON:
You've been misled, Daniel.

1437
01:17:45,212 --> 01:17:47,835
We can talk another time
about how hurtful

1438
01:17:47,973 --> 01:17:49,354
all this has been to me,

1439
01:17:49,492 --> 01:17:52,046
but here we are.

1440
01:17:52,184 --> 01:17:53,807
The archive's safe.

1441
01:17:53,945 --> 01:17:56,223
And now you're going
to tell me the name

1442
01:17:56,361 --> 01:17:58,121
of every confederate at WARDEX

1443
01:17:58,259 --> 01:18:00,745
and what exactly Hugo's
operation is planning.

1444
01:18:01,815 --> 01:18:04,818
But first, without all
this nonsense...

1445
01:18:07,786 --> 01:18:10,444
...you're going to tell me
what you did with the device.

1446
01:18:13,689 --> 01:18:15,863
[tires squealing]

1447
01:18:16,899 --> 01:18:18,901
♪ ♪

1448
01:18:29,739 --> 01:18:31,258
[tires squeal]

1449
01:18:33,674 --> 01:18:35,918
The hell do you think you're
doing driving like that?

1450
01:18:36,056 --> 01:18:38,437
You are Agent Thomas Farley.

1451
01:18:38,575 --> 01:18:41,751
Your ten-digit I.D. code is
3893398887.

1452
01:18:41,889 --> 01:18:43,822
What's the day code?

1453
01:18:45,030 --> 01:18:46,687
Kentucky filly.

1454
01:18:49,241 --> 01:18:51,105
[tires squealing]

1455
01:19:01,564 --> 01:19:03,083
- Agent Grady?
- Yes, ma'am.

1456
01:19:03,221 --> 01:19:04,774
Kentucky filly.
Mr. Scanlon sent for me.

1457
01:19:04,912 --> 01:19:06,224
Follow me.

1458
01:19:10,228 --> 01:19:11,919
[engine shuts off]

1459
01:19:12,057 --> 01:19:14,059
♪ ♪

1460
01:19:32,802 --> 01:19:34,804
♪ ♪

1461
01:19:51,372 --> 01:19:52,649
You're her.

1462
01:19:59,139 --> 01:20:01,382
Margaret Fairchild.

1463
01:20:20,954 --> 01:20:22,403
Jocelyn.

1464
01:20:28,271 --> 01:20:29,721
Jocelyn.

1465
01:20:36,970 --> 01:20:38,385
[gasps]

1466
01:20:38,523 --> 01:20:39,835
[grunting]

1467
01:20:39,973 --> 01:20:41,008
Leave her!

1468
01:20:41,146 --> 01:20:42,630
Stand down.

1469
01:21:00,648 --> 01:21:02,892
I know you.

1470
01:21:13,834 --> 01:21:16,112
I know you, too.

1471
01:21:16,250 --> 01:21:18,045
There's two coming out.

1472
01:21:18,183 --> 01:21:19,805
Don't allow them off the base.

1473
01:21:23,119 --> 01:21:25,673
Hey. Hey. Hey, back inside.

1474
01:21:25,811 --> 01:21:27,434
MARGARET: 
I've waited too long to tell you,

1475
01:21:27,572 --> 01:21:29,022
and now it's too late.

1476
01:21:30,195 --> 01:21:33,026
But I loved you like my own son.

1477
01:21:36,443 --> 01:21:38,548
Stop. Stop. Stop.

1478
01:21:39,584 --> 01:21:41,137
They said we could go up
to the lake on Friday,

1479
01:21:41,275 --> 01:21:43,139
and-and Grandma and Grandpa
will be there,

1480
01:21:43,277 --> 01:21:47,454
and-and Uncle Howard and Bobby
and Teresa and everybody.

1481
01:21:47,592 --> 01:21:49,628
♪ ♪

1482
01:21:59,638 --> 01:22:01,295
How do you know these people?

1483
01:22:01,433 --> 01:22:02,918
MARGARET: I don't.

1484
01:22:03,056 --> 01:22:04,781
You were just talking to them.

1485
01:22:10,580 --> 01:22:12,030
I don't understand
what's happening.

1486
01:22:12,168 --> 01:22:13,929
MARGARET: Just get in!

1487
01:22:20,314 --> 01:22:22,765
- What did you see?
- [engine starts]

1488
01:22:23,904 --> 01:22:25,768
My wife.

1489
01:22:30,152 --> 01:22:31,808
My God.

1490
01:22:32,844 --> 01:22:34,432
What is she?

1491
01:22:35,812 --> 01:22:37,469
Unstoppable.

1492
01:22:37,607 --> 01:22:39,851
♪ ♪

1493
01:22:42,543 --> 01:22:43,959
[beeping]

1494
01:22:49,240 --> 01:22:50,655
DANIEL:
Where are you taking us?

1495
01:22:50,793 --> 01:22:52,588
MARGARET: Kansas City.

1496
01:22:52,726 --> 01:22:54,107
DANIEL: Why there?

1497
01:22:54,245 --> 01:22:56,005
- I have to.
- You don't have to go so...

1498
01:22:56,143 --> 01:22:58,076
- Yeah, uh, yeah, I do.
- Uh, you're enjoying this.

1499
01:22:58,214 --> 01:23:00,734
Yeah, I mean, it-it feels good.
It feels good, and then...

1500
01:23:00,872 --> 01:23:02,839
Yeah, but-but... but you know.
You know.

1501
01:23:02,978 --> 01:23:04,462
I mean, you've been driving
like a maniac

1502
01:23:04,600 --> 01:23:06,015
the last few days, you know.

1503
01:23:06,153 --> 01:23:07,879
- How do you know that?
- I just know things.

1504
01:23:08,017 --> 01:23:09,398
It's just, something happened
to me a couple of days ago,

1505
01:23:09,536 --> 01:23:11,434
and now I-I know things.

1506
01:23:11,572 --> 01:23:12,884
Things I don't really
want to know,

1507
01:23:13,022 --> 01:23:14,058
and all the things
I do want to know,

1508
01:23:14,196 --> 01:23:15,542
I don't really know at all,

1509
01:23:15,680 --> 01:23:17,095
so I've just been
kind of rolling with it.

1510
01:23:17,233 --> 01:23:18,717
You know, like...
Oh, wow, you were in jail?

1511
01:23:18,855 --> 01:23:20,374
- That must have been so...
- Hey, hey!

1512
01:23:20,512 --> 01:23:22,100
- [tires squealing]
- MARGARET: You see what I mean?

1513
01:23:22,238 --> 01:23:24,378
It's crazy. It's crazy.

1514
01:23:24,516 --> 01:23:28,210
I look at somebody,
and I just drop in on them.

1515
01:23:29,245 --> 01:23:31,937
It's like, for a few seconds,
I am them.

1516
01:23:32,076 --> 01:23:33,698
I see the things
that they've lived.

1517
01:23:33,836 --> 01:23:35,769
It's just like it's all
happening to me, too.

1518
01:23:35,907 --> 01:23:37,357
You know, like-like...

1519
01:23:37,495 --> 01:23:38,875
like right now your
shoulder's killing you.

1520
01:23:39,014 --> 01:23:40,739
Yeah, and you-you
just want to yell,

1521
01:23:40,877 --> 01:23:42,362
- "Keep your eyes on the road!"
- Keep your eyes on the road!

1522
01:23:42,500 --> 01:23:44,053
I know, and you can't stop
thinking about Jane,

1523
01:23:44,191 --> 01:23:45,261
and Jane should be back
at the Monastery St. Clare.

1524
01:23:45,399 --> 01:23:46,918
- You're absolutely right.
- Jane?

1525
01:23:47,056 --> 01:23:49,438
But then yesterday,
I'm driving with Jackson,

1526
01:23:49,576 --> 01:23:51,509
and I flashed on you
without seeing you.

1527
01:23:51,647 --> 01:23:53,062
[makes whooshing sound]
It was so strong.

1528
01:23:53,200 --> 01:23:54,753
I dropped right in on you

1529
01:23:54,891 --> 01:23:56,445
without even needing to
look at you, and that was

1530
01:23:56,583 --> 01:23:58,205
the first time that crazy shit
has ever happened to me.

1531
01:23:58,343 --> 01:23:59,862
How long you been
able to do this?

1532
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:01,174
Since yesterday.

1533
01:24:01,312 --> 01:24:02,899
Since the bird.

1534
01:24:03,038 --> 01:24:04,522
- What bird?
- This-this bird.

1535
01:24:04,660 --> 01:24:06,179
Flew in through my window.

1536
01:24:06,317 --> 01:24:08,112
It was beautiful, I looked
at it, and then it-it...

1537
01:24:08,250 --> 01:24:09,216
Was it a cardinal?

1538
01:24:09,354 --> 01:24:10,597
Holy sh... How the...

1539
01:24:10,735 --> 01:24:12,081
You're freaking me the fuck out.

1540
01:24:12,219 --> 01:24:15,050
- [tires squealing]
- [crossing bell dinging]

1541
01:24:18,225 --> 01:24:19,606
I was 20. I was in college.

1542
01:24:19,744 --> 01:24:21,504
You were flunking out,
basically, right?

1543
01:24:21,642 --> 01:24:22,954
Yeah, I-I was pretty smart.

1544
01:24:23,092 --> 01:24:24,335
You were, but it was
the partying.

1545
01:24:24,473 --> 01:24:25,439
It was the partying
and the drugs.

1546
01:24:25,577 --> 01:24:27,027
I mean, ketamine?
Come on, dude.

1547
01:24:27,165 --> 01:24:28,408
- Could you please stop?
- Sorry. I'm stopping.

1548
01:24:28,546 --> 01:24:29,685
- I was 20. I was in college.
- Yes.

1549
01:24:29,823 --> 01:24:32,412
Uh, it was dark, I-I was in bed,

1550
01:24:32,550 --> 01:24:34,793
and I dreamed that
something was watching me.

1551
01:24:34,931 --> 01:24:36,416
I woke up,
and there was this bird.

1552
01:24:36,554 --> 01:24:37,865
- It was a cardinal.
- In the window,

1553
01:24:38,003 --> 01:24:39,764
and it-it looked at me,
and after that,

1554
01:24:39,902 --> 01:24:41,386
everything just changed.

1555
01:24:41,524 --> 01:24:43,802
I saw things:
context, patterns, artifacting.

1556
01:24:43,940 --> 01:24:45,563
I could see it all.

1557
01:24:45,701 --> 01:24:47,461
Arrays and conditionals
just appeared in my head...

1558
01:24:47,599 --> 01:24:48,980
Fully solved. "If P, then Q."

1559
01:24:49,118 --> 01:24:50,637
Exactly. Solved equations

1560
01:24:50,775 --> 01:24:52,156
- without even thinking...
- And you could read

1561
01:24:52,294 --> 01:24:53,398
eight-bit binary data
like it was English,

1562
01:24:53,536 --> 01:24:54,572
- like it was nothing.
- Yeah.

1563
01:24:54,710 --> 01:24:55,642
How do you know all this?

1564
01:24:55,780 --> 01:24:57,333
I don't. You do.

1565
01:24:57,471 --> 01:24:58,610
God, you hated it.

1566
01:24:58,748 --> 01:25:00,405
- It was a curse.
- Yeah.

1567
01:25:00,543 --> 01:25:02,269
I couldn't relate to anybody.

1568
01:25:02,407 --> 01:25:04,029
I lost every friend I ever had
because I-I couldn't stand

1569
01:25:04,168 --> 01:25:05,652
- to be around people.
- [train horn blaring]

1570
01:25:05,790 --> 01:25:07,378
Until you met Jane.

1571
01:25:08,827 --> 01:25:10,829
- [train horn continues blaring]
- [bell clanging]

1572
01:25:10,967 --> 01:25:12,521
"Don't be afraid of
what you don't know."

1573
01:25:12,659 --> 01:25:14,212
- What?
- That's what you said on TV.

1574
01:25:14,350 --> 01:25:15,800
They said I was
talking nonsense.

1575
01:25:15,938 --> 01:25:17,215
I understood every word.

1576
01:25:17,353 --> 01:25:19,010
What happened to us?

1577
01:25:19,148 --> 01:25:21,012
- [Daniel grunts]
- [gasps] Oh, my God.

1578
01:25:21,150 --> 01:25:23,118
- [tires squealing]
- [both grunting]

1579
01:25:23,256 --> 01:25:24,498
Who is it?!

1580
01:25:27,191 --> 01:25:28,364
Boyd, stop!

1581
01:25:28,502 --> 01:25:29,607
Boyd!

1582
01:25:31,954 --> 01:25:33,887
[engine revving]

1583
01:25:34,025 --> 01:25:35,716
[grunts]

1584
01:25:38,857 --> 01:25:39,893
Shit.

1585
01:25:40,997 --> 01:25:42,585
We got to jump! We got to bail!

1586
01:25:42,723 --> 01:25:44,518
I can't!
I'm standing on the brakes!

1587
01:25:48,660 --> 01:25:50,490
Oh, my God! Oh, my God!

1588
01:25:52,699 --> 01:25:53,803
No, no, no, no, no, no, no!

1589
01:25:56,254 --> 01:25:57,807
He's backing up! Get out now!

1590
01:26:08,335 --> 01:26:10,303
[both grunting]

1591
01:26:11,545 --> 01:26:13,271
- [Margaret screaming]
- All right, all right!

1592
01:26:21,831 --> 01:26:23,247
Get to the ladder!

1593
01:26:29,253 --> 01:26:31,186
MARGARET:
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

1594
01:26:31,324 --> 01:26:32,635
DANIEL: Okay.

1595
01:26:32,773 --> 01:26:34,430
[train horn blasting in distance]

1596
01:26:38,779 --> 01:26:40,609
[horn continues blasting]

1597
01:26:40,747 --> 01:26:42,956
[both grunting]

1598
01:26:52,068 --> 01:26:54,243
- [bullets ricocheting]
- [grunting]

1599
01:26:57,004 --> 01:26:58,730
[gasping, whimpering]

1600
01:26:58,868 --> 01:27:01,008
- [horn honking]
- [tires squealing]

1601
01:27:07,325 --> 01:27:08,395
[train horn blaring]

1602
01:27:08,533 --> 01:27:10,535
Go! Jump!

1603
01:27:10,673 --> 01:27:12,434
[metallic creaking]

1604
01:27:14,056 --> 01:27:15,851
[gasps]

1605
01:27:18,440 --> 01:27:20,925
[horn blasting]

1606
01:27:23,445 --> 01:27:25,136
You got to jump!

1607
01:27:26,102 --> 01:27:27,587
Jump! Now!

1608
01:27:32,902 --> 01:27:35,629
- [Daniel straining]
- [breathing heavily]

1609
01:27:37,631 --> 01:27:39,288
[muffled shouting]

1610
01:27:49,712 --> 01:27:52,163
[grunting]

1611
01:27:53,958 --> 01:27:56,271
[heavy, gasping breaths]

1612
01:28:02,242 --> 01:28:03,623
Oh, my God.

1613
01:28:07,454 --> 01:28:10,595
[piano strings resonating]

1614
01:28:11,803 --> 01:28:14,496
I can't breathe.
I can't breathe.

1615
01:28:15,497 --> 01:28:16,808
I can't breathe.

1616
01:28:18,293 --> 01:28:20,433
- It's okay. It's okay.
- I can't breathe.

1617
01:28:20,571 --> 01:28:22,089
- I think you're having a panic attack.
- Oh, my God.

1618
01:28:22,227 --> 01:28:24,333
- It's okay. It's okay.
- Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

1619
01:28:24,471 --> 01:28:26,162
- It's okay. I'm used to 'em.
- [stammers] My hands.

1620
01:28:26,301 --> 01:28:28,026
- We're okay.
- It's like my dad.

1621
01:28:28,164 --> 01:28:29,580
- It's like my dad. My hands.
- No, no, no. No, no, no, no.

1622
01:28:29,718 --> 01:28:31,547
It's like Parkinson's.
It's like Parkinson's.

1623
01:28:31,685 --> 01:28:32,928
It's not the same thing.
It's not that.

1624
01:28:33,066 --> 01:28:34,585
Yes, it is. It's the same.

1625
01:28:34,723 --> 01:28:36,483
No, he couldn't control it.
I can't control it.

1626
01:28:36,621 --> 01:28:38,105
- I can't control it.
- You can.

1627
01:28:38,243 --> 01:28:40,867
[sobbing]: Oh, my God.
I ran away from him.

1628
01:28:41,005 --> 01:28:43,697
- I didn't want to be around him anymore.
- No, no, no. Stop.

1629
01:28:43,835 --> 01:28:45,561
- I want this gone!
- Okay.

1630
01:28:45,699 --> 01:28:48,461
I just want it gone!
I want it gone!

1631
01:28:48,599 --> 01:28:51,187
I want it gone! I just have
no mind of my own anymore!

1632
01:28:51,326 --> 01:28:53,120
Okay, stop! Stop!
Stop talking! Stop.

1633
01:28:53,258 --> 01:28:54,398
Give me your hands.

1634
01:28:54,536 --> 01:28:55,744
- Okay, look at me.
- No, no, no.

1635
01:28:55,882 --> 01:28:57,193
- Look at me.
- I-I'm gonna see things.

1636
01:28:57,332 --> 01:28:58,919
- I'm gonna see things. Please.
- Okay.

1637
01:28:59,057 --> 01:28:59,989
Breathe through your nose.
Breathe through your nose.

1638
01:29:00,127 --> 01:29:01,405
[both taking deep breaths]

1639
01:29:01,543 --> 01:29:03,130
That's it. Okay.

1640
01:29:03,268 --> 01:29:05,201
I can't feel my hands.

1641
01:29:05,340 --> 01:29:07,169
Okay. Okay.

1642
01:29:07,307 --> 01:29:08,998
Okay, give me your hands.
Come on.

1643
01:29:09,136 --> 01:29:10,724
- Come on. Put your hands there.
- [piano strings thrumming]

1644
01:29:10,862 --> 01:29:12,726
Feel that. Okay, you feel that?

1645
01:29:12,864 --> 01:29:14,418
I'm here. I'm here.

1646
01:29:14,556 --> 01:29:16,005
We're here.

1647
01:29:16,143 --> 01:29:17,628
- We're okay.
- Okay.

1648
01:29:18,836 --> 01:29:20,216
- We're okay.
- We're okay.

1649
01:29:20,355 --> 01:29:22,460
We're okay.

1650
01:29:22,598 --> 01:29:25,290
We're okay now. You're okay.

1651
01:29:25,429 --> 01:29:27,431
[heavy breathing continues]

1652
01:29:29,674 --> 01:29:31,676
We're okay.

1653
01:29:31,814 --> 01:29:33,091
Okay.

1654
01:29:33,229 --> 01:29:35,266
[breathing calms down]

1655
01:29:37,855 --> 01:29:39,581
Thank you.

1656
01:29:42,722 --> 01:29:45,000
Kellner called in from a gas
station outside Mount Leonard.

1657
01:29:45,138 --> 01:29:46,381
I'll meet Santiago and his crew.

1658
01:29:46,519 --> 01:29:48,417
We can be there
in a couple hours.

1659
01:29:49,556 --> 01:29:51,040
[Hugo grunts]

1660
01:29:51,178 --> 01:29:53,284
H-Hugo?

1661
01:29:53,422 --> 01:29:54,803
Could everyone leave
the staging area

1662
01:29:54,941 --> 01:29:56,321
for a minute, please?

1663
01:29:56,460 --> 01:29:59,221
- Now, please! Out!
- Yeah. Okay, let's go.

1664
01:29:59,359 --> 01:30:00,878
[sighs]

1665
01:30:03,398 --> 01:30:05,434
- [door opens]
- [groans]

1666
01:30:05,572 --> 01:30:07,194
SCANLON: Hello, Hugo.

1667
01:30:08,403 --> 01:30:10,405
♪ ♪

1668
01:30:12,855 --> 01:30:14,961
Noah, please.

1669
01:30:16,031 --> 01:30:17,929
It's terribly misguided for you
to dive with that thing.

1670
01:30:18,067 --> 01:30:19,931
It's not a magic wand.

1671
01:30:20,069 --> 01:30:21,795
And it's not a weapon,
but it has functions

1672
01:30:21,933 --> 01:30:24,798
very far beyond
your limited use of it.

1673
01:30:24,936 --> 01:30:29,424
Kellner was an experiencer,
wasn't he?

1674
01:30:29,562 --> 01:30:31,426
That's why I
couldn't dive on him.

1675
01:30:31,564 --> 01:30:33,738
Yes.

1676
01:30:33,876 --> 01:30:35,637
He was.

1677
01:30:37,501 --> 01:30:41,505
And In Vivo 17 told
you to recruit him?

1678
01:30:42,816 --> 01:30:44,646
Not in any way you'd understand.

1679
01:30:44,784 --> 01:30:46,371
If this is all their plan, Hugo,

1680
01:30:46,510 --> 01:30:48,960
you can be sure it's
in their interests, not ours.

1681
01:30:49,098 --> 01:30:51,446
That's a very lonely way
to look at the world.

1682
01:30:51,584 --> 01:30:52,964
No, don't condescend to me.

1683
01:30:53,102 --> 01:30:54,518
I'm listening to you, Noah.

1684
01:30:54,656 --> 01:30:56,623
Something I've learned
quite a bit about.

1685
01:30:56,761 --> 01:30:58,176
From your friends?

1686
01:30:58,314 --> 01:30:59,937
Yes.

1687
01:31:00,075 --> 01:31:02,871
They regard empathy as
an evolutionary advantage,

1688
01:31:03,009 --> 01:31:05,494
as the foremost
evolutionary advantage,

1689
01:31:05,632 --> 01:31:09,602
in fact, the core of
animate existence.

1690
01:31:09,740 --> 01:31:11,811
Our rejection of
this understanding

1691
01:31:11,949 --> 01:31:14,123
is leading us to our extinction.

1692
01:31:15,159 --> 01:31:18,162
And is your bleeding heart
why you helped it escape?

1693
01:31:20,129 --> 01:31:21,683
Five years ago.

1694
01:31:21,821 --> 01:31:23,685
That was you, wasn't it?

1695
01:31:25,445 --> 01:31:26,688
Yes.

1696
01:31:27,999 --> 01:31:30,830
The utter insanity
of that act aside,

1697
01:31:30,968 --> 01:31:33,177
how could you lie
to me for five years

1698
01:31:33,315 --> 01:31:34,903
every time you walked
through the door?

1699
01:31:35,041 --> 01:31:37,699
Everything you said to me,
it was all diversion.

1700
01:31:39,701 --> 01:31:42,876
When precisely did
you lose your bearings?

1701
01:31:43,014 --> 01:31:45,361
Around the time you lost yours.

1702
01:31:47,812 --> 01:31:49,400
When you lost her.

1703
01:31:53,784 --> 01:31:56,372
You lost her and almost
immediately were lost to me.

1704
01:31:56,511 --> 01:31:57,753
Because you shut down.

1705
01:31:57,891 --> 01:31:59,341
Do not presume to know me.

1706
01:31:59,479 --> 01:32:00,722
When she died,
you reduced everyone

1707
01:32:00,860 --> 01:32:02,378
to need-to-know, including me.

1708
01:32:02,517 --> 01:32:03,690
Because you were very clear.

1709
01:32:03,828 --> 01:32:05,209
All you needed to know was them,

1710
01:32:05,347 --> 01:32:07,522
and they are not knowable,
not by us.

1711
01:32:07,660 --> 01:32:10,179
They will be.

1712
01:32:10,317 --> 01:32:12,423
In Vivo 17 is nonhuman

1713
01:32:12,561 --> 01:32:14,218
but nearer to God, Noah,
than you or I.

1714
01:32:14,356 --> 01:32:16,323
You don't need to fear them.

1715
01:32:17,324 --> 01:32:19,257
I fear us.

1716
01:32:19,395 --> 01:32:22,433
The entire reason WARDEX exists
is because of our knowledge,

1717
01:32:22,571 --> 01:32:26,644
certain that the human race
cannot accept what we know.

1718
01:32:26,782 --> 01:32:28,439
That truth will upend
all established order

1719
01:32:28,577 --> 01:32:29,889
across the entire world.

1720
01:32:30,027 --> 01:32:32,443
The archive Kellner
stole is a virus

1721
01:32:32,581 --> 01:32:36,758
against which the
world has zero immunity.

1722
01:32:36,896 --> 01:32:39,243
I have spent 35 years
protecting...

1723
01:32:39,381 --> 01:32:40,624
Your own wealth and power--

1724
01:32:40,762 --> 01:32:42,418
that's all you've been protecting.

1725
01:32:42,557 --> 01:32:45,352
Noah. Noah.

1726
01:32:45,490 --> 01:32:47,596
There is an essential need
in all of us to believe

1727
01:32:47,734 --> 01:32:50,979
and an equal need
to be believed.

1728
01:32:51,117 --> 01:32:53,222
You've violated every
standard of evidence.

1729
01:32:53,360 --> 01:32:54,983
You've infantilized anyone

1730
01:32:55,121 --> 01:32:57,675
who only wanted to understand
what they've witnessed.

1731
01:32:57,813 --> 01:33:00,609
You've brutally stifled
their questions,

1732
01:33:00,747 --> 01:33:03,336
shouted them down,
ridiculed and shamed

1733
01:33:03,474 --> 01:33:05,165
and overridden them
for the crime

1734
01:33:05,303 --> 01:33:07,271
of simply being astonished.

1735
01:33:07,409 --> 01:33:10,101
We believe the believers
and then deny the world

1736
01:33:10,239 --> 01:33:12,000
the chance to believe them, too.

1737
01:33:12,138 --> 01:33:14,658
But people keep wondering,
encountering the unknown,

1738
01:33:14,796 --> 01:33:16,418
telling others of
their experiences.

1739
01:33:16,556 --> 01:33:18,834
They are starved for the truth.

1740
01:33:18,972 --> 01:33:22,458
This 79-year terror campaign

1741
01:33:22,597 --> 01:33:26,083
of obfuscation, lies and
cover-up has to end!

1742
01:33:26,221 --> 01:33:28,016
We're ready to show you
a demonstration.

1743
01:33:28,154 --> 01:33:30,501
- HUGO: Get out! Get out!
- Sorry, sir, we have...

1744
01:33:30,639 --> 01:33:32,641
Turn around and get out now!

1745
01:33:38,129 --> 01:33:40,994
Pull up the 12 who didn't
show up to work yesterday.

1746
01:33:41,132 --> 01:33:44,032
I need faces who are
with him right now.

1747
01:33:44,170 --> 01:33:46,655
- Her.
- Grace Zhao, neuro-services.

1748
01:33:46,793 --> 01:33:48,312
- Him.
- Nathan Twinning,

1749
01:33:48,450 --> 01:33:49,865
Hugo's chief aide.

1750
01:33:50,003 --> 01:33:51,453
Got a back door into
their mobile providers.

1751
01:33:51,591 --> 01:33:53,282
Hang on.

1752
01:33:56,354 --> 01:34:00,773
They shut down their phones
last night... right here.

1753
01:34:02,153 --> 01:34:03,914
I'll project their routes
ahead to overlap.

1754
01:34:04,052 --> 01:34:06,710
I can give you the AI model
within a quarter-mile radius.

1755
01:34:06,848 --> 01:34:08,850
[Scanlon breathing heavily]

1756
01:34:13,026 --> 01:34:15,270
[church bell tolling in distance]

1757
01:34:15,408 --> 01:34:17,859
Sister Maura. Sister.

1758
01:34:20,137 --> 01:34:22,139
[indistinct whispering]

1759
01:34:26,143 --> 01:34:27,558
Jane?

1760
01:34:27,696 --> 01:34:29,146
Where are you, Jane?

1761
01:34:29,284 --> 01:34:30,872
- [quiet chatter]
- [bell dinging]

1762
01:34:32,011 --> 01:34:33,564
Does God love us?

1763
01:34:33,702 --> 01:34:36,601
I don't mean, does he love us?
I know he does.

1764
01:34:36,740 --> 01:34:40,467
Does he love only us?

1765
01:34:40,605 --> 01:34:42,780
'Cause Genesis says that
we're his supreme creation,

1766
01:34:42,918 --> 01:34:45,576
but do you think
it's possible that...

1767
01:34:45,714 --> 01:34:47,164
SISTER MAURA: On Earth.

1768
01:34:48,475 --> 01:34:49,614
What?

1769
01:34:49,753 --> 01:34:51,271
Genesis.

1770
01:34:51,409 --> 01:34:56,035
It says we are God's
supreme creation on Earth.

1771
01:34:57,761 --> 01:34:59,417
[bell dinging]

1772
01:35:05,182 --> 01:35:07,184
Do you think there
could be others?

1773
01:35:08,875 --> 01:35:10,912
Yes.

1774
01:35:11,050 --> 01:35:12,637
I would think so.

1775
01:35:12,776 --> 01:35:16,331
Why would he make
such a vast universe,

1776
01:35:16,469 --> 01:35:20,507
yet save it only for us?

1777
01:35:21,612 --> 01:35:26,721
If you found out we
weren't alone, if...

1778
01:35:26,859 --> 01:35:30,345
if someone showed you,
proved it to you...

1779
01:35:32,209 --> 01:35:34,452
...would that frighten you?

1780
01:35:34,590 --> 01:35:37,352
SISTER MAURA:
No. Why? Should it?

1781
01:35:37,490 --> 01:35:40,665
But what if it all collapsed?

1782
01:35:40,804 --> 01:35:43,116
For you and every other
person of faith in the world.

1783
01:35:43,254 --> 01:35:44,255
Then what?

1784
01:35:44,393 --> 01:35:45,567
Oh.

1785
01:35:45,705 --> 01:35:47,949
My dear, Jane.

1786
01:35:48,087 --> 01:35:52,954
I don't think that you ever
doubted your belief in God.

1787
01:35:53,092 --> 01:35:55,991
I think you lost your
faith in people.

1788
01:36:00,616 --> 01:36:03,999
They say you're paying because
you borrowed their phone?

1789
01:36:11,317 --> 01:36:12,939
Are you near the computer?

1790
01:36:13,077 --> 01:36:14,561
SISTER MAURA: Yes.

1791
01:36:14,699 --> 01:36:16,943
What is KCXE?

1792
01:36:17,081 --> 01:36:19,635
Just those letters-- KCXE.

1793
01:36:26,988 --> 01:36:28,921
Remember being a kid?

1794
01:36:29,059 --> 01:36:30,474
Sure.

1795
01:36:30,612 --> 01:36:32,959
Mostly stuff after I was ten.

1796
01:36:38,171 --> 01:36:42,106
Can you tell anything about
me from when I was small?

1797
01:36:46,835 --> 01:36:48,837
♪ ♪

1798
01:37:01,125 --> 01:37:03,127
It's just a fox.

1799
01:37:10,100 --> 01:37:13,103
[brakes squealing]

1800
01:37:16,658 --> 01:37:18,177
DANIEL: No, no, no. No!

1801
01:37:18,315 --> 01:37:21,076
- Stop! Stop!
- No. Daniel!

1802
01:37:21,214 --> 01:37:22,975
- [indistinct chatter]
- [grunting]

1803
01:37:23,113 --> 01:37:24,493
- Let's go. Come with us.
- Hold on.

1804
01:37:24,631 --> 01:37:26,633
- Hold on.
- Let's go.

1805
01:37:26,771 --> 01:37:28,394
I know him. I know him.

1806
01:37:28,532 --> 01:37:30,016
We just got to
check you real quick,

1807
01:37:30,154 --> 01:37:32,501
make sure nobody's
in there with you.

1808
01:37:32,639 --> 01:37:34,193
[electronic trilling]

1809
01:37:38,783 --> 01:37:39,854
[electronic trilling]

1810
01:37:39,992 --> 01:37:41,476
Clear.

1811
01:37:41,614 --> 01:37:43,650
All right, let's load up.

1812
01:37:43,788 --> 01:37:45,376
See, the thing about
fire trucks--

1813
01:37:45,514 --> 01:37:47,862
everyone gets the hell
out of your way.

1814
01:37:48,000 --> 01:37:50,002
♪ ♪

1815
01:38:04,050 --> 01:38:05,880
[Daniel inhales deeply]

1816
01:38:08,399 --> 01:38:10,436
♪ ♪

1817
01:38:36,565 --> 01:38:38,326
I knew you'd make it.

1818
01:38:38,464 --> 01:38:39,914
I'm glad you knew.

1819
01:38:40,052 --> 01:38:41,639
Never a doubt.

1820
01:38:48,819 --> 01:38:50,476
DANIEL: Margaret.

1821
01:38:52,236 --> 01:38:53,651
Margaret.

1822
01:38:56,620 --> 01:38:57,966
Hello, Margaret.

1823
01:39:00,175 --> 01:39:02,384
Do you know who I am?

1824
01:39:02,522 --> 01:39:03,938
Of course. You're Hugo.

1825
01:39:06,802 --> 01:39:08,321
Nathan.

1826
01:39:09,736 --> 01:39:13,292
Chloe. Malik.

1827
01:39:13,430 --> 01:39:15,950
Jordan. Letisha.

1828
01:39:17,158 --> 01:39:18,953
Grace.

1829
01:39:19,091 --> 01:39:20,678
Hi, Terri.

1830
01:39:20,816 --> 01:39:22,749
Kaitlyn. That's Everett.

1831
01:39:32,897 --> 01:39:34,934
♪ ♪

1832
01:39:50,329 --> 01:39:52,400
I think we got it mostly right.

1833
01:39:53,988 --> 01:39:55,368
Margaret.

1834
01:39:55,506 --> 01:39:58,026
Why won't you look at me?

1835
01:39:58,164 --> 01:39:59,683
Because you're-you're the guy.

1836
01:39:59,821 --> 01:40:01,892
You're the guy who
knows everything.

1837
01:40:03,583 --> 01:40:06,345
And I'm... and I'm not ready
to know everything.

1838
01:40:08,209 --> 01:40:11,626
Including, like, why-why my mom
and dad's entire goddamn house

1839
01:40:11,764 --> 01:40:13,076
is just sitting right there!

1840
01:40:13,214 --> 01:40:16,389
What is going on?
Why are you doing this?

1841
01:40:16,527 --> 01:40:18,426
That's where I grew up.
That's where I grew up.

1842
01:40:18,564 --> 01:40:21,739
This is my life.
This is my life.

1843
01:40:21,877 --> 01:40:24,087
And this matters--
what I want, who I am,

1844
01:40:24,225 --> 01:40:27,745
not who I am as you or
him or her, but as me.

1845
01:40:31,956 --> 01:40:33,855
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

1846
01:40:33,993 --> 01:40:36,168
No. No.

1847
01:40:37,824 --> 01:40:40,413
I will not be anyone's religion.

1848
01:40:48,283 --> 01:40:50,596
[sobbing]

1849
01:40:53,357 --> 01:40:55,359
♪ ♪

1850
01:41:05,714 --> 01:41:07,751
♪ ♪

1851
01:41:23,767 --> 01:41:25,907
[whimpers softly]

1852
01:41:51,105 --> 01:41:52,520
My room.

1853
01:41:56,420 --> 01:41:58,250
Oh, my room.

1854
01:42:25,277 --> 01:42:27,762
Why would you build all of this?

1855
01:42:27,900 --> 01:42:30,316
To create a passage.

1856
01:42:32,422 --> 01:42:34,389
To return you to your experience

1857
01:42:34,527 --> 01:42:37,358
in the most familiar way
possible.

1858
01:42:37,496 --> 01:42:39,705
What experience?

1859
01:42:41,983 --> 01:42:44,158
The one you shared
with Margaret.

1860
01:42:45,918 --> 01:42:47,057
I shared?

1861
01:42:47,195 --> 01:42:49,473
I am not going back there.

1862
01:42:49,611 --> 01:42:51,268
- Hugo.
- How much do you remember about that night?

1863
01:42:51,406 --> 01:42:53,097
I don't remember, and I
don't want to remember,

1864
01:42:53,236 --> 01:42:54,789
and I don't want you
making me remember.

1865
01:42:54,927 --> 01:42:56,998
- Okay. Oh, my...
- HUGO: Wait. Wait.

1866
01:42:57,136 --> 01:42:58,931
Wait.

1867
01:42:59,069 --> 01:43:00,898
Everything that happened to you
on the 23rd of February, 1996,

1868
01:43:01,036 --> 01:43:02,521
- is blocked.
- I don't want to know anything about it.

1869
01:43:02,659 --> 01:43:03,970
The only way for you
to know what's next

1870
01:43:04,108 --> 01:43:05,800
is to understand
what came before.

1871
01:43:05,938 --> 01:43:07,181
I don't want to talk about it.
I don't. Stop, stop, stop.

1872
01:43:07,319 --> 01:43:08,734
And then you'll know
your purpose.

1873
01:43:08,872 --> 01:43:10,080
Please don't make me.
I don't want to hear it.

1874
01:43:10,218 --> 01:43:11,012
You won't be a
passenger anymore.

1875
01:43:11,150 --> 01:43:12,738
I told you no! [gasps]

1876
01:43:17,570 --> 01:43:20,884
You have the gift
but no control.

1877
01:43:21,022 --> 01:43:23,024
No understanding
of your purpose.

1878
01:43:23,162 --> 01:43:24,750
Not a clue as to
what your situation

1879
01:43:24,888 --> 01:43:27,097
will demand of you beyond today.

1880
01:43:27,235 --> 01:43:29,582
The only way for you
to acquire it

1881
01:43:29,720 --> 01:43:33,103
is to go back to
where it all began.

1882
01:43:33,241 --> 01:43:34,898
To go home.

1883
01:43:41,042 --> 01:43:45,080
And when you do, Margaret,
you'll know everything.

1884
01:43:45,219 --> 01:43:48,360
More than what was ever
humanly possible.

1885
01:44:09,657 --> 01:44:11,866
They gifted each of you.

1886
01:44:12,004 --> 01:44:14,972
Margaret, what was dormant
in you for most of your life

1887
01:44:15,110 --> 01:44:17,768
was activated only yesterday.

1888
01:44:18,804 --> 01:44:21,358
And yours, 15 years ago.

1889
01:44:21,496 --> 01:44:23,464
They gave you fluency
in the language

1890
01:44:23,602 --> 01:44:25,914
in which the book of
the universe is written:

1891
01:44:26,052 --> 01:44:27,813
mathematics.

1892
01:44:27,951 --> 01:44:31,403
Taught it to you, imbued it
so you could understand them.

1893
01:44:32,438 --> 01:44:36,477
And they imbued you so
you could understand us.

1894
01:44:38,789 --> 01:44:41,171
It's the two of you.

1895
01:44:41,309 --> 01:44:42,759
[chuckles]

1896
01:44:42,897 --> 01:44:46,418
It's always been
just the two of you.

1897
01:44:55,012 --> 01:44:57,014
[quiet, indistinct chatter]

1898
01:45:08,716 --> 01:45:10,304
You can direct it

1899
01:45:10,442 --> 01:45:12,616
or feel where it
wants to take you.

1900
01:45:13,893 --> 01:45:15,861
It can find what
you're looking for.

1901
01:45:15,999 --> 01:45:18,864
It'll be an instrument
of your will.

1902
01:45:19,002 --> 01:45:21,315
But you must give
yourself over to it.

1903
01:45:22,661 --> 01:45:24,973
I'll find out what's
happening to me.

1904
01:45:27,493 --> 01:45:28,874
What?

1905
01:45:29,012 --> 01:45:30,531
It's gonna be okay.

1906
01:45:30,669 --> 01:45:32,153
I promise.

1907
01:45:39,333 --> 01:45:41,335
♪ ♪

1908
01:45:49,343 --> 01:45:50,930
Whatever happens, Daniel,

1909
01:45:51,068 --> 01:45:53,070
- don't you let go.
- Don't you let go.

1910
01:45:56,280 --> 01:45:57,730
Margaret.

1911
01:46:00,250 --> 01:46:02,356
Look around the room
one more time.

1912
01:46:03,874 --> 01:46:05,876
♪ ♪

1913
01:46:09,293 --> 01:46:12,745
You're a ten-year-old girl
asleep in your bed.

1914
01:46:12,883 --> 01:46:14,713
Something woke you up,
didn't it?

1915
01:46:14,851 --> 01:46:16,059
Yes.

1916
01:46:16,197 --> 01:46:17,888
So what did you do?

1917
01:46:18,924 --> 01:46:20,960
I sang my song.

1918
01:46:23,066 --> 01:46:26,069
[humming "Someday My Prince Will Come"]

1919
01:46:36,493 --> 01:46:40,048
<i>♪ And away to his castle ♪</i>

1920
01:46:40,186 --> 01:46:42,568
<i>♪ We'll go ♪</i>

1921
01:46:42,706 --> 01:46:46,400
<i>♪ To be happy forever ♪</i>

1922
01:46:46,538 --> 01:46:49,195
<i>♪ I know ♪</i>

1923
01:46:49,333 --> 01:46:53,303
<i>♪ And the birds will sing. ♪</i>

1924
01:46:59,240 --> 01:47:01,276
♪ ♪

1925
01:47:03,796 --> 01:47:06,143
I can see them.

1926
01:47:06,281 --> 01:47:08,283
Right over there.

1927
01:47:08,422 --> 01:47:10,251
They're coming into the room.

1928
01:47:12,805 --> 01:47:14,807
♪ ♪

1929
01:47:16,740 --> 01:47:19,743
[gruff, heavy breathing nearby]

1930
01:47:36,450 --> 01:47:37,761
[chitters softly]

1931
01:48:01,440 --> 01:48:03,477
♪ ♪

1932
01:48:06,480 --> 01:48:08,309
DANIEL: No, no, no,
don't go with them.

1933
01:48:08,447 --> 01:48:09,828
They're not animals.

1934
01:48:09,966 --> 01:48:11,899
Don't go with them.
They're not animals.

1935
01:48:12,037 --> 01:48:13,521
They're not animals!

1936
01:48:13,659 --> 01:48:15,281
- It's okay. It's okay.
- [panting] They're not.

1937
01:48:15,419 --> 01:48:19,216
They-they present
as animals to calm us.

1938
01:48:24,463 --> 01:48:27,121
When I walked through the glass,

1939
01:48:27,259 --> 01:48:31,159
it was like this
curtain of warm water.

1940
01:48:33,990 --> 01:48:36,371
And the snow...

1941
01:48:36,510 --> 01:48:39,720
was so warm on my feet.

1942
01:48:41,549 --> 01:48:44,379
[long, slow gasp]

1943
01:48:44,518 --> 01:48:46,485
The house.

1944
01:48:52,733 --> 01:48:55,321
"Hansel and Gretel."

1945
01:49:12,028 --> 01:49:14,030
[soft electrical warbling]

1946
01:49:20,415 --> 01:49:22,452
♪ ♪

1947
01:49:25,386 --> 01:49:27,422
[soft electrical warbling]

1948
01:49:30,702 --> 01:49:32,704
[soft whooshing]

1949
01:49:40,574 --> 01:49:42,127
[gruff, heavy breathing nearby]

1950
01:49:42,265 --> 01:49:44,785
[young Margaret breathing heavily]

1951
01:49:57,349 --> 01:50:00,076
[chittering]

1952
01:50:10,811 --> 01:50:13,503
[rapid, gasping breaths]

1953
01:50:25,135 --> 01:50:26,792
Shh.

1954
01:50:32,660 --> 01:50:34,869
Hold my hand.

1955
01:50:43,844 --> 01:50:46,122
[young Daniel's breathing slowing down]

1956
01:50:53,612 --> 01:50:55,649
♪ ♪

1957
01:50:58,513 --> 01:51:00,550
[trembling breaths]

1958
01:51:03,104 --> 01:51:05,175
- [soft electrical whooshing]
- [gasps]

1959
01:51:12,010 --> 01:51:14,012
[soft electrical crackling]

1960
01:51:27,197 --> 01:51:30,200
[soft whooshing, crackling]

1961
01:51:32,030 --> 01:51:34,032
- [sharp whoosh]
- [gasps]

1962
01:51:43,282 --> 01:51:45,319
♪ ♪

1963
01:51:48,184 --> 01:51:50,186
[soft whirring]

1964
01:51:53,741 --> 01:51:55,605
[soft whooshing]

1965
01:52:06,064 --> 01:52:08,066
[breathing heavily]

1966
01:52:11,655 --> 01:52:13,071
Whoa.

1967
01:52:15,073 --> 01:52:16,730
Whoa.

1968
01:52:33,539 --> 01:52:35,576
♪ ♪

1969
01:52:54,457 --> 01:52:56,252
Hello, Hugo.

1970
01:52:59,669 --> 01:53:01,809
It's so nice to
finally know you.

1971
01:53:02,879 --> 01:53:04,743
[tires squealing]

1972
01:53:04,881 --> 01:53:06,883
♪ ♪

1973
01:53:15,996 --> 01:53:17,998
[indistinct chatter]

1974
01:53:19,275 --> 01:53:20,863
They found us.

1975
01:53:21,001 --> 01:53:23,210
[labored breathing]

1976
01:53:23,348 --> 01:53:24,832
HUGO:
<i>Are they out front or out back?</i>

1977
01:53:24,970 --> 01:53:26,420
Most likely on all sides.

1978
01:53:26,558 --> 01:53:29,733
Okay, give me the, uh...
the-the-the thingy.

1979
01:53:29,872 --> 01:53:33,392
Thermal imaging showed 43
heat signatures inside here.

1980
01:53:33,530 --> 01:53:35,222
This whole area's an
industrial decay zone.

1981
01:53:35,360 --> 01:53:37,741
No other structure has
more than five people in it.

1982
01:53:39,398 --> 01:53:41,711
[heavy, labored breathing]

1983
01:53:45,370 --> 01:53:46,992
- [groans]
- Hey.

1984
01:53:47,130 --> 01:53:49,477
[grunts] Get on with it.

1985
01:53:54,275 --> 01:53:56,277
[whirring]

1986
01:54:05,873 --> 01:54:07,806
[electronic trilling, beeping]

1987
01:54:23,235 --> 01:54:25,237
♪ ♪

1988
01:54:33,832 --> 01:54:35,040
[hushed]: No one move.

1989
01:54:35,178 --> 01:54:37,387
No one make a sound.

1990
01:54:37,525 --> 01:54:38,941
They can't see us.

1991
01:54:42,496 --> 01:54:44,222
Give it to me.

1992
01:54:49,744 --> 01:54:51,505
This is not right.

1993
01:54:54,577 --> 01:54:58,201
They can't see us,
but they can see this.

1994
01:54:59,202 --> 01:55:01,929
We need to move now.

1995
01:55:02,067 --> 01:55:04,898
This is not gonna last long.
We got to go right now.

1996
01:55:15,253 --> 01:55:16,633
[hushed]: Look. They can't see me.

1997
01:55:16,771 --> 01:55:18,118
They can't see us. Let's go.

1998
01:55:18,256 --> 01:55:19,533
Quiet, quiet.

1999
01:55:19,671 --> 01:55:20,914
Through the back doors.
Any back door.

2000
01:55:21,052 --> 01:55:22,916
Go quiet. Go quiet.
Down the alley.

2001
01:55:23,054 --> 01:55:25,125
- Let's go. Let's go.
- Quiet.

2002
01:55:25,263 --> 01:55:28,024
Everybody, stop moving.

2003
01:55:28,162 --> 01:55:30,164
[rapid footsteps]

2004
01:55:36,170 --> 01:55:38,138
There. Look there.

2005
01:55:40,588 --> 01:55:42,211
Oh, God, I'm losing it.

2006
01:55:42,349 --> 01:55:44,006
I'm losing it.
You need to go faster.

2007
01:55:44,144 --> 01:55:45,800
- Get to the fire truck.
- I can't hold on.

2008
01:55:45,939 --> 01:55:47,112
- I can't hold...
- We got to go.

2009
01:55:47,250 --> 01:55:48,838
Stay on the light.

2010
01:55:51,945 --> 01:55:53,118
MARGARET: I can't hold on.

2011
01:55:54,257 --> 01:55:56,466
- [groaning]
- [glass shattering]

2012
01:55:59,055 --> 01:56:00,160
- [loud thud]
- [groans]

2013
01:56:00,298 --> 01:56:01,471
[Margaret gasps]

2014
01:56:01,609 --> 01:56:03,335
- [creaking]
- [grunts]

2015
01:56:03,473 --> 01:56:04,923
DANIEL: Let's go.

2016
01:56:05,061 --> 01:56:06,994
[device thrumming]

2017
01:56:08,133 --> 01:56:10,066
There. There.
Stay on the light.

2018
01:56:13,414 --> 01:56:15,658
- Stay on the light.
- The light! The light!

2019
01:56:18,005 --> 01:56:20,835
[groaning]

2020
01:56:26,324 --> 01:56:28,705
[groaning]

2021
01:56:33,538 --> 01:56:35,505
[engine starts]

2022
01:56:37,783 --> 01:56:39,509
[siren blaring]

2023
01:56:39,647 --> 01:56:41,684
[urgent chatter]

2024
01:56:43,168 --> 01:56:45,205
SANTIAGO: Hang on.
Grab ahold of something.

2025
01:56:49,071 --> 01:56:50,865
[frantic chatter]

2026
01:56:51,004 --> 01:56:53,075
